WEBVTT

00:17.686 --> 00:21.147
MAN: <i>I told you before
I didn't want you to read this crap.</i>

00:21.356 --> 00:23.441
<i>I never saw such rotten
crap in my life.</i>

00:23.650 --> 00:26.653
<i>Where do you get this shit?
Who sells it to you?</i>

00:27.237 --> 00:30.573
<i>I'm talking to you, young man. You
wanna answer me when I'm talking to you.</i>

00:30.782 --> 00:33.702
<i>Remember who puts the frigging bread
on the table around here, don't you?</i>

00:33.910 --> 00:36.246
WOMAN: <i>Stan, don't be too hard
on him, all the kids read them.</i>

00:36.454 --> 00:38.164
STAN:
<i>My boy isn't all the kids.</i>

00:38.623 --> 00:40.458
<i>You wanna know
where this is going, Billy?</i>

00:40.667 --> 00:42.836
<i>In the garbage.
Right into the frigging garbage.</i>

00:43.044 --> 00:45.046
<i>Now, you got any smart mouth
about that?</i>

00:45.255 --> 00:45.922
(lightning crashes)

00:46.131 --> 00:48.758
BILLY: <i>I don't see how it's any worse
than the books you keep in your dresser.</i>

00:48.967 --> 00:51.761
<i>Those ones under your underwear,
those sex books.</i>

00:52.595 --> 00:54.472
- Stan, you didn't have to--
- Hit him?

00:54.681 --> 00:58.476
Not only do I find out he's reading this crap,
he's a goddamn little snoop as well.

00:58.727 --> 01:00.478
- No, it wasn't like that!
- (lightning crashes)

01:00.687 --> 01:03.148
You said for me to get your cuff links.
It was on Sunday.

01:03.356 --> 01:04.274
(lightning crashes)

01:04.482 --> 01:06.317
The windows are open downstairs,
I better go down and close them.

01:06.526 --> 01:07.777
- The rain will get in.
- No, I'll do it.

01:07.986 --> 01:09.696
I got some garbage
I wanna throw away.

01:09.904 --> 01:13.199
Daddy, please don't
throw it away. I'm sorry.

01:13.408 --> 01:17.037
The next time, young man, I find you with
a worthless piece of shit like this again...

01:17.245 --> 01:19.622
...you won't sit down
for a week, buddy boy.

01:19.831 --> 01:21.082
Remember that.

01:21.833 --> 01:22.959
Tuck in.

01:23.168 --> 01:24.919
♪♪

01:29.466 --> 01:31.217
(thunder rolls,
lightning crashes)

01:39.142 --> 01:40.852
(lightning crashes)

01:41.186 --> 01:42.687
That takes care of that.

01:43.855 --> 01:45.523
WOMAN:
Stan, don't you think you were...

01:46.566 --> 01:48.276
...a little hard on him?

01:48.485 --> 01:51.237
Did you see that crap?
All that horror crap?

01:51.446 --> 01:53.490
Things coming out of crates
and eating people?

01:53.698 --> 01:57.285
Dead people coming back to life?
People turning into weeds, for chrissake?

01:57.494 --> 02:00.413
- Well, yes, I did, but I--
- STAN: <i>Well, you want him reading that stuff?</i>

02:00.622 --> 02:02.248
- Well, no, but--
- STAN: <i>All right, then.</i>

02:02.916 --> 02:04.501
I took care of it.

02:05.335 --> 02:07.420
That's why God
made fathers, babe.

02:08.463 --> 02:10.215
- That's why God made fathers.
- (lightning crashes)

02:10.423 --> 02:12.175
♪♪

02:12.967 --> 02:14.719
(lightning crashes)

02:15.345 --> 02:17.305
I hope you rot in hell.

02:17.972 --> 02:19.724
(lightning crashes)

02:25.021 --> 02:26.773
(cackling laughter)

02:38.159 --> 02:39.911
(chanting)

02:46.251 --> 02:48.002
(laughing)

03:03.518 --> 03:05.436
♪♪

03:10.441 --> 03:13.820
(lightning crashes)

03:44.350 --> 03:45.602
(lightning crashes)

04:01.743 --> 04:02.869
(lightning crashes)

04:03.119 --> 04:04.871
(cackling laughter)

04:14.297 --> 04:16.048
(choir singing)

04:24.599 --> 04:26.351
♪♪

04:33.233 --> 04:34.984
(grandfather clock chiming)

04:36.945 --> 04:39.239
Do you really think she'll
be out, Aunt Sylvia?

04:39.447 --> 04:41.616
Of course she will, Richard.
You know that.

04:42.116 --> 04:45.119
You can set your watch by her.
Six o'clock on the dot.

04:45.328 --> 04:49.916
Pass those scones, Cass.
You're such a hog.

04:51.793 --> 04:54.545
You married a great hog, Henry.

04:54.754 --> 04:57.131
But then I suppose you know that,
don't you?

04:57.590 --> 05:01.803
Our Cass has always had
such extremely healthy appetites.

05:03.346 --> 05:04.639
Who's coming out, Cass?

05:04.847 --> 05:08.977
You mean Cass hasn't told you about
dotty old Great-Aunt Bedelia...

05:09.185 --> 05:11.020
...the patriarch of our clan?

05:11.437 --> 05:13.481
Isn't she the one
that was supposed to have...?

05:15.441 --> 05:18.319
- Well....
- Supposed to have murdered her father?

05:18.736 --> 05:19.529
Yes.

05:20.989 --> 05:22.240
(tires squealing)

05:24.492 --> 05:26.119
SYLVIA:
<i>Bedelia is my aunt...</i>

05:26.327 --> 05:29.163
<i>...which means that she's
Richard and Cass' great-aunt...</i>

05:29.372 --> 05:32.125
<i>...which also means
that she's older than God.</i>

05:32.458 --> 05:36.379
But her father, Nathan Grantham,
was even older and meaner than that.

05:36.587 --> 05:40.591
All a bunch of dirty vultures...

05:41.050 --> 05:46.931
...just waiting to get
your hands on my money.

05:47.140 --> 05:50.226
He was hysterically jealous
of Bedelia all his life.

05:50.476 --> 05:52.645
Complete Freudian relationship.

05:52.937 --> 05:56.858
Then when he was about 184,
he had a stroke...

05:57.066 --> 06:00.278
...and lucky Bedelia,
she got to nurse him full time.

06:00.778 --> 06:02.780
Then she met a fella.

06:03.239 --> 06:05.908
Yes, sir, a real
September courtship.

06:06.492 --> 06:07.660
September courtship?

06:07.869 --> 06:10.455
<i>This was October or November
at the very least.</i>

06:10.788 --> 06:13.708
He was 75. Aunt Bedelia is...?

06:13.958 --> 06:15.084
Never mind, my dears.

06:15.293 --> 06:19.005
The point is, Henry, Bedelia
loved her rather elderly beau...

06:19.213 --> 06:21.549
<i>...and her own father
had him murdered.</i>

06:21.758 --> 06:22.759
(match ignites)

06:22.967 --> 06:26.971
RICHARD: <i>Yarbro was the guy's name,
and he supposedly died...</i>

06:27.180 --> 06:28.222
(gunshot)

06:28.431 --> 06:30.725
...in a "hunting accident."

06:31.351 --> 06:33.102
<i>That's what's
on the books, anyway.</i>

06:33.311 --> 06:35.605
For Bedelia,
it was the last straw.

06:36.481 --> 06:39.567
She bashed her father's head in
with a marble ashtray.

06:41.944 --> 06:43.363
So rumor has it.

06:44.864 --> 06:46.657
SYLVIA:
<i>Well, however it happened...</i>

06:46.866 --> 06:50.119
<i>...it was good riddance
to some extremely bad rubbish.</i>

06:50.328 --> 06:53.039
And my lovely niece
and my handsome nephew...

06:53.247 --> 06:56.459
<i>...have very good reasons for
being pleased at old Nathan's death.</i>

06:56.667 --> 07:01.214
There was no trouble about
the will. Share and share alike.

07:01.422 --> 07:03.174
♪♪

07:05.635 --> 07:10.306
SYLVIA: <i>And now, every Father's Day,
every single Father's Day since his death...</i>

07:10.515 --> 07:13.768
<i>...for seven long years,
she returns to this house...</i>

07:13.976 --> 07:15.520
<i>...the scene of her crime.</i>

07:16.145 --> 07:17.271
(tires squealing)

07:17.480 --> 07:18.773
- Is that--?
- SYLVIA: Oh, yes.

07:19.857 --> 07:21.818
You can almost set
your watch by her.

07:22.026 --> 07:23.194
(grandfather clock chiming)

07:23.403 --> 07:24.445
(brakes squealing)

07:24.654 --> 07:25.738
(laughing)

07:25.947 --> 07:28.324
Screech to a halt, as they say.

07:28.741 --> 07:31.119
- Do you think she really did it?
- Oh, yes.

07:31.953 --> 07:33.621
I know she did it.

07:33.830 --> 07:34.580
(emergency brake ratcheting)

07:34.789 --> 07:38.876
SYLVIA: <i>Bedelia was always very unstable,
even when she was much younger.</i>

07:39.377 --> 07:43.840
<i>And after the death of her gentleman friend,
she grew steadily worse.</i>

07:46.175 --> 07:47.176
HANK:
<i>Why Father's Day?</i>

07:47.385 --> 07:51.556
Because that was the day of the tragedy,
and she is overwhelmed with her own guilt.

07:51.764 --> 07:52.723
(tapping)

07:52.932 --> 07:57.520
SYLVIA: <i>She will go to her father's grave
and meditate for about an hour.</i>

07:57.770 --> 07:59.355
And then she will come inside...

07:59.564 --> 08:04.026
...and we will all sit down
to a nice baked-ham dinner...

08:04.277 --> 08:05.820
...the three of us--

08:06.070 --> 08:09.657
Oh, I'm so sorry, Henry. The four of us.

08:09.866 --> 08:14.162
<i>--who now owe her so very much.</i>

08:18.583 --> 08:19.876
♪♪

08:20.084 --> 08:21.836
(porch light squeaking)

08:42.899 --> 08:47.028
NATHAN [IN VOICE-OVER]:
<i>Where's my cake?</i>

08:47.487 --> 08:51.032
<i>I want my cake.</i>

08:55.495 --> 09:01.959
<i>Where's my cake, Bedelia?</i>

09:02.168 --> 09:06.547
<i>Where's my Father's Day cake?</i>

09:06.756 --> 09:10.009
<i>I want my cake...</i>

09:10.218 --> 09:13.054
<i>...you dirty bitch.</i>

09:13.930 --> 09:16.098
<i>I'm going to have it.</i>

09:18.809 --> 09:19.852
Bedelia!

09:21.229 --> 09:23.814
<i>It's Father's Day.</i>

09:24.065 --> 09:26.484
Where's my cake?

09:26.692 --> 09:30.029
<i>You promised me my cake!</i>

09:30.238 --> 09:33.032
Bedelia, I'm your father...

09:33.241 --> 09:35.660
<i>...and you're supposed to be
taking care of me.</i>

09:35.993 --> 09:37.995
I don't hear you.
I said, I don't hear you!

09:38.204 --> 09:41.332
Bedelia, you bitch!

09:41.624 --> 09:44.961
<i>What do you think
I've got you here for?</i>

09:45.169 --> 09:48.631
<i>You're just like all the others.</i>

09:49.090 --> 09:52.718
You're nothing but
a bunch of vultures.

09:52.927 --> 09:54.679
- (yelling)
- (cane tapping)

09:56.430 --> 10:00.851
Bedelia! I want my cake.

10:01.143 --> 10:03.020
Bedelia!

10:03.229 --> 10:07.316
Where's my Father's Day cake?

10:09.402 --> 10:12.029
Happy Father's Day!

10:24.166 --> 10:25.918
(birds and crickets chirping)

10:31.424 --> 10:32.383
(bottle thudding)

10:35.928 --> 10:37.597
Don't be stupid.

10:38.222 --> 10:39.348
(sighs)

10:42.476 --> 10:44.353
Happy Father's Day.

10:54.488 --> 10:55.448
(sniffles)

10:58.034 --> 11:00.202
God, I didn't know
I had it in me.

11:00.411 --> 11:04.707
I'm your daughter, right?
You bootlegger. Killer, murderer!

11:04.915 --> 11:07.001
Ungrateful bastard.

11:12.423 --> 11:14.759
<i>Shouldn't have killed
Peter, you know.</i>

11:15.426 --> 11:17.261
He was a man, right, a real man.

11:17.470 --> 11:20.848
See, everything I wanted,
he wanted for me.

11:21.390 --> 11:24.977
You stupid bastard.
You screwed it all up.

11:25.186 --> 11:27.772
You screwed up my mother,
you screwed me up.

11:31.817 --> 11:34.987
<i>You got me so mad,
drove me crazy.</i>

11:35.404 --> 11:39.659
"I want my cake, Bedelia.
You bitch!"

11:39.867 --> 11:42.286
You called me a bitch.

11:42.495 --> 11:44.747
<i>Sylvia fixed it all.</i>

11:44.955 --> 11:48.584
Ashtray back in place,
chair overturned.

11:48.793 --> 11:50.252
(clicks tongue, inhales sharply)

11:51.087 --> 11:54.090
You took a fall, Daddy,
a bad fall.

11:54.382 --> 11:56.467
Nobody could catch us, nobody.

11:57.134 --> 12:00.846
You taught me. You taught Sylvia.
You taught us all.

12:05.976 --> 12:07.395
(chuckles)

12:13.234 --> 12:14.985
(clicks tongue, mumbles)

12:16.946 --> 12:18.364
It's so peaceful here.

12:18.572 --> 12:20.241
♪♪

12:20.700 --> 12:22.201
(screaming)

12:22.451 --> 12:25.705
No! No!

12:25.913 --> 12:27.665
(screaming)

12:30.042 --> 12:33.796
Where's my cake, Bedelia?

12:34.004 --> 12:35.005
(screaming)

12:36.298 --> 12:39.427
I want my cake.

12:41.679 --> 12:43.431
(screaming)

12:44.181 --> 12:48.644
It's Father's Day, Bedelia.

12:48.894 --> 12:52.273
I want my cake.

12:56.360 --> 12:58.112
(grandfather clock chiming)

13:01.866 --> 13:03.617
♪♪

13:14.795 --> 13:18.674
SYLVIA:
<i>Cass! Cass, turn that down!</i>

13:19.216 --> 13:23.929
Cass, turn that down
and turn it down right now.

13:32.605 --> 13:34.523
Shall I glaze
the ham now, ma'am?

13:34.815 --> 13:37.568
No, Mrs. Danvers,
you'll have to wait.

13:37.777 --> 13:39.779
<i>Ms. Grantham
has not yet arrived.</i>

13:39.987 --> 13:42.990
And you will remember that
today is a very special day for her.

13:43.240 --> 13:44.492
Yes, ma'am.

13:48.996 --> 13:52.833
- Ain't life grand, Mrs. D.?
- SYLVIA: <i>I do hope she's all right.</i>

13:53.292 --> 13:55.795
Sometimes she loses
track of time.

13:56.003 --> 13:57.755
♪♪

13:58.506 --> 13:59.298
(door shuts)

14:01.217 --> 14:02.343
(exhales sharply)

14:05.805 --> 14:06.847
(match ignites)

14:23.614 --> 14:24.448
(car door shuts)

14:36.126 --> 14:36.961
(switch clicks)

14:49.598 --> 14:50.850
HANK: <i>Aunt Bedelia?</i>

14:53.227 --> 14:55.104
Ms. Grantham, are you around?

15:17.585 --> 15:18.335
(match ignites)

15:35.269 --> 15:36.228
(rumbling)

15:37.438 --> 15:39.189
♪♪

15:46.864 --> 15:48.282
(branches clattering)

15:57.041 --> 15:57.708
(thudding)

15:58.959 --> 16:00.711
(squeaking)

16:17.645 --> 16:18.520
(bottle clattering)

16:31.617 --> 16:32.743
Whoa...
(grunts)

16:32.952 --> 16:33.827
Jesus.

16:34.828 --> 16:36.580
(rumbling)

16:36.789 --> 16:38.540
♪♪

16:45.089 --> 16:46.423
(sliding)

16:57.017 --> 16:58.769
(sliding)

17:13.784 --> 17:15.536
(sliding)

17:18.329 --> 17:19.707
- (sliding)
- (screaming)

17:19.915 --> 17:20.833
(squishing)

17:22.751 --> 17:23.961
(chuckling)

17:24.877 --> 17:26.630
(insects chittering)

17:29.800 --> 17:33.345
Where's my cake?

17:33.929 --> 17:37.516
I want it. It's mine.

17:37.850 --> 17:39.935
♪♪

17:56.535 --> 17:57.619
(music stops)

17:58.787 --> 18:00.247
(footsteps echoing)

18:00.914 --> 18:01.665
(sighs)

18:02.249 --> 18:05.502
- Where is he?
- My dear, I really couldn't say.

18:05.753 --> 18:09.423
No doubt he's still out at the grave,
hobnobbing with your Aunt Bedelia...

18:09.631 --> 18:11.800
<i>...getting her side
of the story, I expect.</i>

18:12.051 --> 18:15.888
Well, I want him. And I
want my dinner. I'm hungry.

18:16.096 --> 18:18.265
Well, go get him, then.

18:19.767 --> 18:21.226
You go, Richard.

18:22.394 --> 18:25.272
He's your husband.
I don't even like him.

18:25.481 --> 18:27.149
SYLVIA:
<i>I'll go and get him.</i>

18:27.775 --> 18:31.028
After all, he's
such a sweet boy.

18:31.820 --> 18:32.863
(laughing)

18:33.072 --> 18:34.823
♪♪

18:39.203 --> 18:41.580
Mrs. Danvers? Mrs. D--

18:43.832 --> 18:45.334
Mrs. Danvers.

18:59.181 --> 19:00.933
(cooking pots bubbling)

19:03.519 --> 19:04.770
Mrs. Dan--

19:04.978 --> 19:06.730
♪♪

19:11.735 --> 19:13.487
(screaming)

19:13.821 --> 19:15.447
(panting)

19:16.990 --> 19:20.160
I want my cake.

19:20.619 --> 19:21.245
(neck snapping)

19:21.453 --> 19:23.288
(grandfather clock chiming)

19:30.963 --> 19:32.714
♪♪

19:38.762 --> 19:41.932
Where is she?
And where the hell is Hank?

19:43.600 --> 19:47.146
Go see, Richard. Please? Please?

19:47.396 --> 19:49.690
RICHARD:
<i>Look, my daring sister...</i>

19:49.898 --> 19:51.400
...he is your hick--

19:52.234 --> 19:55.154
Husband, I mean.
You go look for him.

19:55.362 --> 19:57.781
Richard, I'm scared,
and it's dark out there.

19:58.699 --> 20:00.993
Look, I just wanna get
another bottle of wine, okay?

20:01.201 --> 20:03.245
Please, Richard.

20:06.915 --> 20:08.750
All right. Come on.

20:09.793 --> 20:11.044
<i>Come on.</i>

20:16.884 --> 20:18.635
♪♪

20:19.803 --> 20:21.722
Are we conserving energy?

20:41.742 --> 20:42.534
(screaming)

20:42.743 --> 20:45.078
NATHAN:
It's Father's Day...

20:45.412 --> 20:48.290
...and I got my cake.

20:48.498 --> 20:50.083
Oh, my God!

20:50.417 --> 20:53.837
Happy Father's Day.

20:54.046 --> 20:55.797
(evil laughing)

21:05.515 --> 21:07.267
♪♪

21:21.490 --> 21:25.535
(distant rumbling coming closer)

21:27.454 --> 21:28.497
(explosion)

21:29.289 --> 21:31.959
Holy old Jesus.

21:44.721 --> 21:48.934
That's a meteor. I'd be dipped
in shit if that ain't a meteor.

22:10.580 --> 22:12.165
Oh, shit!

22:20.048 --> 22:22.968
I wonder how much they'd pay
for it up at the college?

22:23.176 --> 22:26.930
[IN VOICE-OVER] <i>I wonder how much
they'd pay for it up at the college?</i>

22:27.139 --> 22:28.890
♪♪

22:33.937 --> 22:37.566
Well, damn fine one,
Mr. Verrill.

22:37.774 --> 22:38.775
Uh-huh.

22:41.111 --> 22:45.365
How does $50 sound?

22:45.615 --> 22:49.369
Not a cent less than 200 bucks.

22:50.579 --> 22:53.123
- Seventy-five?
- Two hundred.

22:53.582 --> 22:56.335
Anita Verrill
didn't raise no idjits.

22:59.296 --> 23:00.505
Keep a-countin'.

23:01.214 --> 23:03.008
JORDY:
<i>Not a cent less than 200.</i>

23:03.342 --> 23:06.345
My meteor, my price.

23:09.473 --> 23:12.559
Pay off that bank loan.
That's the ticket.

23:13.810 --> 23:16.772
Got to cool the
son of a bitch off. Yeah.

23:19.608 --> 23:21.360
♪♪

23:21.985 --> 23:23.737
(water running)

23:41.004 --> 23:42.756
(splashing, hissing)

23:55.394 --> 23:57.938
Oh, you done it now,
Jordy Verrill.

23:58.230 --> 23:59.689
You lunkhead.

24:00.315 --> 24:02.818
[IN VOICE-OVER]
<i>You lunkhead.</i>

24:03.026 --> 24:05.570
Two hundred dollars?

24:05.862 --> 24:07.823
<i>For a broken meteor?</i>

24:08.031 --> 24:11.284
<i>Mr. Verrill, you must be joking.</i>

24:11.827 --> 24:12.577
(slam echoing)

24:12.786 --> 24:14.955
I wouldn't give you 2 cents.

24:15.872 --> 24:17.624
JORDY:
<i>Jordy Verrill, you lunkhead.</i>

24:18.458 --> 24:23.380
Verrill luck's always in,
and you spell that kind of luck B-A-D.

24:25.549 --> 24:28.009
Still, I got to try.

24:34.349 --> 24:36.101
(liquid pours, sizzles)

24:39.604 --> 24:40.605
(clattering)

24:43.483 --> 24:45.235
(liquid pours, sizzles)

24:47.946 --> 24:48.989
(clattering)

24:51.241 --> 24:52.701
Meteor shit.

24:59.040 --> 25:00.792
(sizzling)

25:06.256 --> 25:06.965
(bucket clattering)

25:08.925 --> 25:11.344
Maybe I can glue it together
in the morning.

25:15.640 --> 25:17.559
(bucket clattering)

25:27.152 --> 25:29.404
MAN [ON TV]:
<i>The World Wrestling Federation champion...</i>

25:29.654 --> 25:31.490
<i>...defending his title here
at Madison Square Garden.</i>

25:31.698 --> 25:34.159
<i>That's Sika, the Samoan
Number 1, in control.</i>

25:34.367 --> 25:37.078
<i>Oh, a kick nails him. Oh, baby.</i>

25:37.287 --> 25:41.583
<i>Everything went but the
kitchen sink. Look out.</i>

25:41.791 --> 25:43.126
(bell ringing)

25:43.335 --> 25:47.506
<i>That huge 300-pounder
drop kicked right on out.</i>

25:47.714 --> 25:49.466
♪♪

25:49.966 --> 25:53.595
MAN [ON TV]: <i>Hit to the midsection now,
Backlund reverses it.</i>

25:54.429 --> 25:56.640
<i>Once again,
it's gone to the buckle.</i>

25:58.975 --> 26:02.562
<i>Backlund working on the left arm
of Samoan Number 1.</i>

26:10.487 --> 26:13.448
<i>Hit to the midsection.
Backlund has him up.</i>

26:14.199 --> 26:16.618
<i>Oh, forget about it.</i>

26:17.244 --> 26:18.245
(spitting)

26:20.664 --> 26:22.123
JORDY: <i>Jesus Christ.</i>

26:32.509 --> 26:35.470
(phone clicking, dialing)

26:40.767 --> 26:42.519
♪♪

26:49.109 --> 26:52.153
DOCTOR:
<i>I'm sorry, Mr. Verrill.</i>

26:52.946 --> 26:54.781
Those fingers have...

26:55.949 --> 26:57.325
...got to come off.

27:14.301 --> 27:15.176
Uh-oh.

27:22.434 --> 27:23.476
(compartment slams shut)

27:24.269 --> 27:29.524
DOCTOR:
This is going to be extremely painful...

27:29.733 --> 27:32.235
...Mr. Verrill.

27:33.361 --> 27:35.113
(shouting)

27:46.374 --> 27:48.084
Oh, Jordy Verrill...

27:48.877 --> 27:51.755
...you lunkhead, you been....

27:52.088 --> 27:54.633
MAN [ON TV]: <i>We're gonna try--
No, Backlund behind him.</i>

27:55.800 --> 27:57.052
<i>Throws him up.</i>

27:58.637 --> 28:00.180
<i>Pushes back.</i>

28:01.056 --> 28:04.100
(bell ringing)

28:18.365 --> 28:20.075
(eerie warbling)

28:26.122 --> 28:27.707
WOMAN 1 [ON TV]:
<i>I thought I'd find you up.</i>

28:28.500 --> 28:31.920
<i>Oh, stop that. Now, don't cry,
this isn't gonna do a bit for you.</i>

28:32.128 --> 28:35.173
WOMAN 2: <i>Oh, I'm crying because
Aunt Mattie and Aleck make me so mad.</i>

28:35.382 --> 28:37.884
WOMAN 1:
<i>Aleck and Aunt Mattie? Fiddlesticks.</i>

28:39.219 --> 28:41.596
Golly, don't it itch.

28:43.473 --> 28:46.101
<i>Well, that's
Verrill luck, all right.</i>

28:46.726 --> 28:50.021
Always in, always bad.

28:50.230 --> 28:52.941
WOMAN 1: <i>But there's a difference
between dreaming and doing.</i>

28:53.149 --> 28:55.026
<i>The dreamers just
sit around and moon...</i>

28:55.235 --> 29:00.198
<i>...about how wonderful it would be
if only things were different.</i>

29:00.657 --> 29:03.451
<i>The years roll on,
and they grow old.</i>

29:03.660 --> 29:07.622
<i>By and by, they forget everything,
even about their dreams.</i>

29:07.831 --> 29:10.500
WOMAN 2: <i>I don't want to be like that.
I want to be somebody.</i>

29:10.750 --> 29:14.170
WOMAN 1: <i>Oh, everyone laughed at us,
as they did at all the other pioneers.</i>

29:14.379 --> 29:17.340
<i>They said this country
would never be anything but a wilderness.</i>

29:17.549 --> 29:21.720
<i>We didn't believe that.
We were going to make a new country.</i>

29:22.095 --> 29:26.975
<i>Besides, we wanted to see
our dreams come true.</i>

29:27.183 --> 29:29.018
WOMAN 2:
<i>Granny, it must have been wonderful.</i>

29:29.227 --> 29:30.478
WOMAN 1:
<i>It was wonderful.</i>

29:30.687 --> 29:35.150
<i>But don't you think for one single minute
that it was easy, Esther Blodgett.</i>

29:35.567 --> 29:38.069
<i>We burned in summer
and we froze in winter...</i>

29:38.278 --> 29:41.114
<i>...but we kept right on going,
and we didn't complain...</i>

29:41.406 --> 29:44.159
<i>...because we were doing
what we wanted to do.</i>

29:44.576 --> 29:46.119
<i>Can you understand that?</i>

29:46.411 --> 29:47.537
No.

29:49.372 --> 29:54.085
No, no, no, no, no,
no, no, no, no, no.

29:54.419 --> 29:56.504
No. No.

29:57.255 --> 29:59.007
(clattering)

30:03.178 --> 30:06.514
There you are, you sucker.
I knowed you was in there someplace.

30:22.071 --> 30:24.699
MAN 1 [ON TV]: <i>The Tristate Ecumenical
Council presents</i> Let There Be Light...

30:24.908 --> 30:27.160
<i>...with Father Martin Burdine.</i>

30:28.244 --> 30:31.039
MAN 2: <i>Many of you
have made the great breakthrough...</i>

30:31.456 --> 30:34.709
<i>...one giant step,
the faith decision.</i>

30:34.918 --> 30:35.668
Needed that.

30:35.877 --> 30:38.838
MAN 2: <i>You then said,
"My troubles are over."</i>

30:39.339 --> 30:40.590
<i>Not true.</i>

30:41.841 --> 30:44.511
<i>Look up. Lift up your head.</i>

30:45.303 --> 30:47.472
<i>You will succeed.</i>

30:47.972 --> 30:51.100
<i>Be confident of this one thing:</i>

30:51.309 --> 30:54.729
<i>That God, who has begun
a good thing in you...</i>

30:55.021 --> 30:56.815
<i>...will complete it.</i>

30:57.065 --> 30:58.066
MAN 3:
<i>Prerecorded.</i>

30:58.858 --> 30:59.776
(sighs)

31:05.448 --> 31:06.825
I'm growing.

31:07.033 --> 31:08.785
♪♪

31:27.345 --> 31:28.346
(television chiming)

31:30.348 --> 31:32.559
Oh, my God. What a dr--

31:37.272 --> 31:38.106
(whimpering)

31:43.778 --> 31:44.737
(clattering)

31:46.656 --> 31:48.408
(yelling)

31:49.701 --> 31:51.452
(tap squeaking, water running)

32:07.010 --> 32:09.846
Oh, no, not there!

32:11.139 --> 32:14.017
- Jordy.
- Daddy?

32:14.225 --> 32:15.518
FATHER:
<i>Jordy.</i>

32:20.940 --> 32:22.317
But you're dead.

32:25.820 --> 32:26.821
You've been dead...

32:27.947 --> 32:30.074
...Christ, three years almost.

32:30.450 --> 32:33.077
You ain't gonna get
into that tub, are you?

32:35.330 --> 32:38.291
<i>It's the water
that it wants, Jordy.</i>

32:38.875 --> 32:42.754
<i>Don't you know that?
You get in that water, Jordy...</i>

32:43.254 --> 32:45.798
...you might as well
sign your death warrant.

32:46.966 --> 32:50.720
I'm a goner already,
Daddy, ain't I?

32:51.638 --> 32:54.724
<i>I got the stuff
from out of that meteor on me...</i>

32:56.434 --> 32:59.729
...and I'm gone, ain't I?

33:01.272 --> 33:02.148
Daddy?

33:07.028 --> 33:08.029
Daddy?

33:13.910 --> 33:14.786
(groaning)

33:17.830 --> 33:19.582
(water continues running)

33:33.930 --> 33:35.264
Ah....

33:35.473 --> 33:36.849
(splashing)

33:37.183 --> 33:40.895
JORDY: <i>Oh, better.
Oh, that's lots better. Oh.</i>

33:41.729 --> 33:42.981
<i>Oh, that's good.</i>

33:43.189 --> 33:44.941
(sighing and grunting)

33:45.149 --> 33:46.818
(bird chirping)

33:47.026 --> 33:49.070
MAN [ON TV]:
<i>And now it's time for the Farm Report...</i>

33:49.278 --> 33:51.656
<i>...brought to you
by Grainger Farm Supply...</i>

33:51.948 --> 33:54.701
<i>...the home of all your feed
and farm supplies.</i>

33:55.702 --> 33:58.496
<i>Grain prices closed mixed
after rising most of the session...</i>

33:58.705 --> 34:01.457
<i>...in reaction
to some of the positive export news.</i>

34:01.833 --> 34:04.127
<i>Analysts said prices were centered
in the new highs...</i>

34:04.335 --> 34:07.630
<i>...in the late-session selling
by commission houses and local traders...</i>

34:07.839 --> 34:10.382
<i>...who sought to take profits
from the early advances.</i>

34:11.426 --> 34:16.139
<i>Pork-belly prices and most livestock prices
fell on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.</i>

34:16.973 --> 34:22.728
<i>In quiet trading, cotton for delivery
this month settled at 63.2 cents a pound.</i>

34:23.771 --> 34:26.482
Please. Please.

34:27.108 --> 34:29.277
Please, God...

34:30.110 --> 34:32.112
...let my luck be in...

34:32.905 --> 34:36.617
...just this once.

34:37.284 --> 34:38.870
Please, God...

34:39.786 --> 34:41.789
...just this once.

34:42.831 --> 34:43.958
(gunshot)

34:45.752 --> 34:47.420
MAN [ON TV]:
<i>And in today's weather...</i>

34:48.004 --> 34:52.050
<i>...well, not much for the outdoor types,
but you farmers are going to love this.</i>

34:52.550 --> 34:54.052
<i>The current 30-day forecast...</i>

34:54.260 --> 34:56.929
<i>...released by the U.S.
meteorological station at Portland...</i>

34:57.138 --> 35:00.058
<i>...calls for moderating temperatures
and lots of rain.</i>

35:00.391 --> 35:03.728
<i>Castle County is going to turn green
so fast in the next month...</i>

35:04.228 --> 35:06.314
<i>...that it's going to be almost miraculous.</i>

35:06.522 --> 35:08.274
♪♪

35:15.073 --> 35:16.824
(lightning crashes)

35:37.595 --> 35:38.930
(knocking)

35:39.639 --> 35:40.640
- MAN: <i>Wentworth?</i>
- (groans)

35:40.848 --> 35:41.891
(knocking)

35:42.100 --> 35:43.935
All right, all right.

35:44.977 --> 35:46.938
(knocking)

35:47.146 --> 35:49.190
- MAN: <i>Wentworth?</i>
- All right, I said.

35:51.234 --> 35:52.985
- (knocking)
- (groans)

36:00.159 --> 36:03.454
That may work on TV, mister,
but I can bench-press 300 pounds.

36:03.663 --> 36:07.083
You'd better get your foot out of the door,
or you're gonna lose about half of it.

36:07.542 --> 36:08.626
Don't call me "mister."

36:08.835 --> 36:11.921
You know damn well who I am,
so let's not play any games, huh?

36:12.421 --> 36:15.383
- Come on, get out of here.
- Listen to me, Harry, and listen carefully.

36:15.591 --> 36:19.303
Unless you let me in and talk to me,
something very nasty...

36:19.512 --> 36:21.597
...is going to happen to Rebecca.

36:22.265 --> 36:27.228
So nasty that your little mind
can barely conceive of it.

36:29.063 --> 36:30.356
(chuckles)

36:33.359 --> 36:35.361
You found out. All right.

36:35.820 --> 36:38.531
Becky and I were gonna sit down
and tell you pretty soon anyway.

36:38.739 --> 36:40.575
You know, some of
these cables are loose, Harry?

36:40.783 --> 36:43.828
I'm surprised you didn't notice a change
in the quality of your picture.

36:50.793 --> 36:53.379
You know, you ought to be grateful to us,
you know that?

36:53.963 --> 36:55.756
I mean, if you ever loved her,
you don't now.

36:56.591 --> 36:59.427
There won't be any alimony,
none of that community-property shit.

36:59.635 --> 37:00.511
She just wants out.

37:00.720 --> 37:04.182
Well, I don't know whether I ever loved her
or not, Harry. That doesn't matter.

37:04.432 --> 37:08.853
The point is, I keep what is mine.
No exception to that rule, ever.

37:10.897 --> 37:14.734
No exceptions, Harry. Never.

37:18.988 --> 37:21.574
What did you mean when you said
something nasty was gonna happen?

37:21.782 --> 37:24.202
You really should take better care
of this equipment.

37:24.452 --> 37:26.913
At least get a maintenance cartridge,
and dust off the heads.

37:27.121 --> 37:29.207
Talk to me right now.

37:30.666 --> 37:33.669
Take your hand off me,
right now.

37:34.879 --> 37:36.130
All right, fine.

37:39.800 --> 37:41.761
Got something
I want you to hear.

37:44.263 --> 37:47.934
WOMAN [ON RECORDING]:
<i>Harry, he's got me in....</i>

37:48.142 --> 37:51.520
<i>Please come. Please.</i>

37:52.104 --> 37:54.106
<i>He's got me in....</i>

37:54.315 --> 37:56.567
<i>If you don't come, the....</i>

37:56.776 --> 38:00.238
<i>Please, Harry. Please come.</i>

38:00.446 --> 38:03.241
I had to stop it there,
I couldn't bear to record any more.

38:04.033 --> 38:05.326
What have you done with her?

38:07.203 --> 38:09.288
Talk to me, you son of a bitch,
or I'm gonna kill you.

38:09.497 --> 38:12.875
You kill me and you'll never find out.
Now, don't get naughty, Harry.

38:13.084 --> 38:16.921
If I fall down on this floor
and hit my head on that hard marble...

38:17.129 --> 38:19.048
...why, I could fracture my skull.

38:19.257 --> 38:21.175
- Fine with me.
- And then you'll never know.

38:21.384 --> 38:24.679
And believe me, Mr. True-Love,
you'll want to know.

38:24.887 --> 38:27.932
Because by 11 this morning,
it's gonna be too late.

38:30.810 --> 38:32.561
♪♪

38:34.313 --> 38:36.732
VICKERS: <i>I love the ocean,
except when the tide is out.</i>

38:36.941 --> 38:39.819
<i>Then it has that
kind of rotten smell.</i>

38:40.027 --> 38:41.821
HARRY: <i>I just don't understand
what you're trying to prove.</i>

38:42.029 --> 38:43.781
(laughing)

38:45.241 --> 38:47.535
VICKERS:
I'm not trying to prove a thing.

38:47.743 --> 38:51.747
It may be, on some subjects,
that I'm not entirely sane.

38:52.081 --> 38:56.252
The subject of what is mine, for example,
I am not sane at all.

38:56.752 --> 38:59.463
(engine revving)

39:04.552 --> 39:06.304
(camera whirring)

39:11.100 --> 39:12.852
(seagulls cawing)

39:16.355 --> 39:20.443
VICKERS: <i>Now, this is Comfort Point,
and I call my beach house Comfort Station.</i>

39:21.319 --> 39:24.405
<i>- Is that camp or kitsch, Harry?</i>
HARRY: <i>It's stupid.</i>

39:24.947 --> 39:29.368
VICKERS:
Unkind, Harry, unkind.

39:29.869 --> 39:33.372
Well, I won't hold it against you.

39:33.873 --> 39:35.624
Come on, up this way.

39:36.417 --> 39:38.169
(whistling "Camptown Races")

39:40.629 --> 39:45.426
Harry, the maiden fair is waiting
for her knight in shining corduroy.

39:45.634 --> 39:46.844
Come on.

39:50.639 --> 39:53.142
Harry, here's something
I think you'll find interesting.

39:53.392 --> 39:54.935
You see that down there?

39:56.729 --> 39:58.147
Is that...?

39:58.397 --> 39:59.273
What?

40:00.733 --> 40:03.277
<i>The burial mound
of my lady fair?</i>

40:03.486 --> 40:04.862
Oh, m--

40:06.322 --> 40:07.448
Could be.

40:09.116 --> 40:10.868
♪♪

40:23.381 --> 40:25.132
VICKERS: <i>You notice
how the water creeps in?</i>

40:25.925 --> 40:28.761
<i>Even when the tide's out,
the water creeps in.</i>

40:29.303 --> 40:31.138
I don't know what the hell
you think you're--

40:34.975 --> 40:35.851
Now, look.

40:37.603 --> 40:39.855
This has gone
just about far enough.

40:40.064 --> 40:40.731
(laughing)

40:40.940 --> 40:43.067
No, Harry,
not nearly far enough.

40:43.317 --> 40:45.569
Now, if you're thinking
of becoming a hero...

40:45.778 --> 40:48.072
...I suggest that you remember
the lady fair.

40:53.327 --> 40:54.703
Jump into that hole.

40:54.912 --> 40:56.664
♪♪

41:02.503 --> 41:05.005
- No.
- Then you force me to shoot you, Harry.

41:07.550 --> 41:08.426
Sorry.

41:11.429 --> 41:12.263
(pistol hammer cocks)

41:21.230 --> 41:23.107
Good boy, Harry. Good boy.

41:29.321 --> 41:32.575
Now, Harry,
I want you to kneel down...

41:33.075 --> 41:35.119
...and start pulling the sand into the hole.

41:37.121 --> 41:40.916
Uh-uh. No way.
Go ahead, shoot me if you want to.

41:41.125 --> 41:43.502
<i>- You're not gonna bury me alive.</i>
- Not a bad idea.

41:44.170 --> 41:46.547
<i>Not exactly what I
had in mind, though.</i>

41:46.964 --> 41:50.426
All I wanna do is incapacitate you.
Then you can see Becky.

41:54.096 --> 41:55.014
I don't believe you.

41:55.473 --> 41:57.349
VICKERS: <i>I always keep
my promises, Harry.</i>

41:57.516 --> 41:59.143
And I do have the gun, don't I?

42:02.480 --> 42:05.608
- Help!
- Yell all you want, Harry.

42:05.983 --> 42:09.069
Comfort Point is
very private. I own it all.

42:09.278 --> 42:11.780
Help! Help! Help!

42:11.989 --> 42:13.782
Help!

42:13.991 --> 42:15.451
(birds flapping)

42:15.659 --> 42:17.119
Nobody's gonna hear you, Harry.

42:18.329 --> 42:20.080
Nobody's gonna hear anything.

42:20.623 --> 42:21.624
(gunshot)

42:24.919 --> 42:26.378
Now, do what I told you.

42:28.923 --> 42:30.674
(seagulls cawing)

42:35.095 --> 42:36.847
(waves crashing)

42:43.729 --> 42:44.939
(tapping)

42:47.816 --> 42:49.193
(groaning)

42:51.445 --> 42:52.279
There.

42:54.156 --> 42:57.117
Sort of like being buried
in wet cement, huh?

42:57.451 --> 42:58.619
Can't move your arms.

42:59.662 --> 43:01.038
Don't have any leverage.

43:02.289 --> 43:03.999
Go ahead, Harry, try to move.

43:05.000 --> 43:06.752
(chuckling)

43:07.711 --> 43:08.921
(sighs)

43:13.300 --> 43:16.178
You know, I could really...

43:17.346 --> 43:20.349
...cover you all the way up,
couldn't I, Harry?

43:20.599 --> 43:24.270
I could make Harry all gone.

43:25.479 --> 43:26.605
(spitting)

43:26.814 --> 43:30.359
Oh, no. No, no, no.
I wouldn't do that.

43:31.151 --> 43:32.695
Here, let me get that.

43:33.529 --> 43:36.115
Get that out of you.
There you are. That's good.

43:36.448 --> 43:39.159
No, I keep my promises.

43:44.039 --> 43:45.791
(yelps)

43:46.292 --> 43:47.626
Oh, Jesus. Get out.

43:47.835 --> 43:49.336
(engine rumbling)

43:49.545 --> 43:52.798
Get out of here.
Just-- Richard!

43:57.094 --> 43:58.971
Richard, would you
get it out of here?

43:59.430 --> 44:00.306
Well...

44:01.432 --> 44:03.100
...found a friend, Harry?

44:03.475 --> 44:04.268
(chuckling)

44:04.476 --> 44:06.228
(singing "I'm Just Wild
About Harry")

44:07.396 --> 44:10.399
Hey, come on, Richard.
Get it out of here.

44:10.649 --> 44:12.735
He's just
getting revenge, Harry...

44:13.110 --> 44:17.573
...for all the relatives of his that you ate,
baked and stuffed, at Ma Maison.

44:17.990 --> 44:20.784
Bad fellow, you.
Oh, you bad fellow. Go on.

44:21.160 --> 44:22.369
Get out of there.

44:22.578 --> 44:24.330
(chuckling)

44:25.205 --> 44:26.165
(sighs)

44:31.086 --> 44:31.754
(blowing)

44:31.962 --> 44:34.214
Money. Look, I have money.

44:36.175 --> 44:38.844
I'll give you anything.
Just get me out of this hole, all right?

44:39.053 --> 44:40.929
Well, I have
something here, Harry.

44:42.056 --> 44:43.015
Take your mind off of it.

44:43.223 --> 44:48.020
- Come on, Richard, please--
- It's showtime.

44:48.228 --> 44:49.104
(woman shouting)

44:51.565 --> 44:53.942
Oh, my-- Becky?

44:54.985 --> 44:57.404
Isn't that great video?
I love this stuff.

44:57.613 --> 44:59.948
Now, just look at the quality
of that picture, Harry.

45:00.157 --> 45:02.660
- Somebody!
- HARRY: <i>Becky.</i>

45:02.868 --> 45:04.787
- No.
- Becky!

45:04.995 --> 45:06.497
Can't hear you.

45:06.914 --> 45:10.417
I'm sorry. She lost a coin toss.
I had to bury her further down the beach.

45:10.834 --> 45:13.420
<i>Couldn't even leave her a monitor,
it would have shorted out by now.</i>

45:13.629 --> 45:17.257
No, no, no. No, that's a trick.
You son of a bitch!

45:17.633 --> 45:20.427
That's some kind of
special-effects trick, isn't it?

45:20.636 --> 45:22.763
If you'll just take a look
at the VCR back there....

45:23.305 --> 45:24.890
Oh, I'm sorry,
you can't turn your head.

45:25.307 --> 45:28.977
Let me assure you, Harry,
the VCR is not on "play," it's on "record."

45:29.186 --> 45:30.312
I'm gonna save this stuff.

45:30.896 --> 45:32.690
<i>The two of you
are part of my home movies.</i>

45:32.898 --> 45:33.816
HARRY:
<i>You're insane.</i>

45:35.109 --> 45:37.194
VICKERS: <i>Won't be long now,
huh? Not long at all.</i>

45:37.861 --> 45:38.862
Oh, my God.

45:40.864 --> 45:41.740
You are insane.

45:41.949 --> 45:45.619
I promised that you'd see Becky again.
I kept my promise. Is that insane?

45:46.453 --> 45:49.540
- (gasping, struggling)
- Oh, you bastard. You bastard.

45:49.748 --> 45:51.750
VICKERS: <i>There's a chance
you can get out of this, Harry.</i>

45:52.000 --> 45:55.671
The tide might even set you free. It depends
on how long you keep your cool...

45:55.879 --> 45:57.923
...how long you hold your breath,
you see, Harry.

45:59.216 --> 46:02.803
- The water's so cold, so salty.
- (panting)

46:03.053 --> 46:05.264
You're underneath,
and you're holding your breath...

46:05.472 --> 46:08.058
...waiting for that wave covering you
to go back out...

46:08.267 --> 46:11.186
- ...so you can snatch a quick breath...
- (panting)

46:13.522 --> 46:15.357
...before the next wave comes in.

46:15.566 --> 46:17.317
(shouting)

46:19.445 --> 46:22.489
Now, you've got a chance, Harry,
if you don't lose your head.

46:22.740 --> 46:25.576
- Now, it looks like she's losing hers.
<i>- Oh, God, no!</i>

46:28.537 --> 46:31.206
VICKERS: <i>Feel how hard
your heart is beating, Harry?</i>

46:31.415 --> 46:32.332
(Becky coughing)

46:32.541 --> 46:33.917
VICKERS: <i>How fast?</i>

46:34.793 --> 46:37.755
<i>Now, that's gonna make it harder
for you to hold your breath, isn't it?</i>

46:39.506 --> 46:41.258
(Becky coughing)

46:42.384 --> 46:43.844
BECKY: <i>Oh, God.</i>

46:44.052 --> 46:46.430
Oh, the tide.

46:47.848 --> 46:49.057
<i>Coming in.</i>

46:50.851 --> 46:52.227
It's getting late, Harry.

46:53.187 --> 46:56.023
- Guess I'll have to trot along now.
- Wait, wait, wait, wait, wait.

46:56.231 --> 46:58.942
No. You enjoy the show.

46:59.151 --> 47:01.236
<i>At least until the monitor
shorts out.</i>

47:01.487 --> 47:04.281
All right, come on, come on.
Stop it, stop it, stop it!

47:04.573 --> 47:07.701
Sorry, Harry.
I really can't stay.

47:09.036 --> 47:10.037
(Becky coughing)

47:10.245 --> 47:14.249
- Come on. Come back here, Richard.
- BECKY: <i>Oh, God.</i>

47:14.750 --> 47:16.502
(Becky coughing)

47:18.796 --> 47:20.255
Come on, Richard!

47:20.464 --> 47:22.216
(engine rumbling)

47:25.219 --> 47:27.638
Come on, Richard, please!

47:29.681 --> 47:32.100
<i>Oh, God.</i>
(coughing)

47:32.309 --> 47:37.397
<i>Harry. Harry.</i>
(coughing)

47:43.779 --> 47:45.531
(waves crashing)

47:52.996 --> 47:54.748
(electricity crackling)

48:07.469 --> 48:09.221
- (waves crashing)
- (bucket clunking)

48:22.901 --> 48:24.611
♪♪

48:26.822 --> 48:28.574
(camera whirring)

48:33.912 --> 48:35.664
(water burbling)

48:42.462 --> 48:44.214
(engine rumbling)

48:54.850 --> 48:57.728
(door opening, closing)

49:07.029 --> 49:08.780
(whirring)

49:20.834 --> 49:22.669
<i>No, no.</i>
(crying)

49:23.837 --> 49:25.589
(waves crashing)

49:28.050 --> 49:29.801
(breathing heavily)

49:34.097 --> 49:35.849
(Becky crying indistinctly)

49:38.352 --> 49:40.395
(humming)

49:40.604 --> 49:42.356
(chuckling)

49:45.734 --> 49:47.486
- (coughing)
- (laughing)

49:51.657 --> 49:56.578
<i>Oh, no! No! No!</i>

49:56.787 --> 49:58.538
(Becky screaming)

50:01.875 --> 50:04.127
BECKY: <i>No, no, no.</i>
(crying)

50:04.586 --> 50:07.673
<i>God, no, no, no.</i>

50:07.881 --> 50:09.633
(waves crashing)

50:22.771 --> 50:23.689
Oh, my God.

50:23.897 --> 50:25.649
(waves rumbling)

50:33.281 --> 50:35.033
- (shouting)
- (waves crashing)

50:39.121 --> 50:40.247
HARRY:
<i>Richard.</i>

50:45.836 --> 50:48.964
<i>I'm gonna get you.
You hear me, Richard?</i>

50:49.172 --> 50:52.217
<i>You hear me, Richard?
I'm gonna get you.</i>

50:53.176 --> 50:55.262
You've gotta hold
your breath there, Harry.

50:58.598 --> 51:00.517
Gotta hold your breath.

51:00.851 --> 51:02.602
(bubbling)

51:13.530 --> 51:14.448
(bubbling)

51:14.656 --> 51:16.408
(wind whistling)

51:22.039 --> 51:23.790
(waves crashing)

51:25.542 --> 51:27.294
(seagulls cawing)

51:34.593 --> 51:36.344
♪♪

51:53.653 --> 51:55.530
The current pulled him out.

52:16.676 --> 52:18.303
That's what happened, all right.

52:18.512 --> 52:20.263
(waves crashing)

52:21.389 --> 52:23.725
The current pulled him out.
He's gone.

52:25.852 --> 52:26.520
(bucket clattering)

52:27.896 --> 52:29.356
HARRY [IN VOICE-OVER]:
<i>Richard.</i>

52:32.317 --> 52:34.069
(waves breaking)

52:39.616 --> 52:41.368
(seagulls cawing)

52:42.869 --> 52:44.621
♪♪

53:02.472 --> 53:06.268
<i>Never mind where I told you to stand,
you stand where I tell you.</i>

53:06.476 --> 53:08.562
<i>Kid's so dumb,
he doesn't know what time it is.</i>

53:08.812 --> 53:10.814
<i>- By the way, what time is it?</i>
- MAN 2: <i>I don't know.</i>

53:11.022 --> 53:13.191
MAN 1: <i>Stand here and
keep your eye on the ball.</i>

53:13.775 --> 53:15.527
♪♪

53:25.162 --> 53:28.582
Now, let me see, where is...?

53:29.624 --> 53:33.628
Boy, if that damn maid has been
moving my stuff again, I swear I'll--

53:33.837 --> 53:35.422
HARRY'S VOICE:
<i>Richard.</i>

54:08.997 --> 54:11.041
Undertow has carried them away.

54:11.791 --> 54:12.959
Saved me the trouble.

54:23.178 --> 54:24.429
Come off it.

54:32.938 --> 54:35.732
No need to get jumpy.

54:36.358 --> 54:37.984
They're all gone.

54:38.276 --> 54:40.654
Blub, blub, blub,
blub, blub, blub, blub.

54:42.280 --> 54:44.032
(humming)

54:56.711 --> 54:58.463
(shower running)

55:08.515 --> 55:10.267
(water burbling)

55:19.567 --> 55:25.323
(footsteps squishing)

55:39.754 --> 55:42.507
(squishing footsteps continue)

55:53.810 --> 55:55.353
(shower stops)

55:59.482 --> 56:01.234
(squishing footsteps continue)

56:07.282 --> 56:09.034
(whirring)

56:17.167 --> 56:18.668
(whirring stops)

56:32.390 --> 56:34.142
(squishing footsteps continue)

56:40.523 --> 56:41.816
Who's out there?

56:42.025 --> 56:43.777
♪♪

56:51.951 --> 56:52.994
Wentworth?

56:58.500 --> 56:59.959
That you, Wentworth?

57:01.586 --> 57:04.714
May I remind you, dear boy,
I have the gun?

57:05.298 --> 57:07.425
(squishing footsteps continue)

57:08.218 --> 57:09.594
VICKERS:
<i>Wentworth?</i>

57:10.470 --> 57:12.722
I suggest you get out of here...

57:13.723 --> 57:14.599
...or I'll shoot you.

57:17.310 --> 57:18.436
<i>Fair warning.</i>

57:19.479 --> 57:21.815
Wentworth? I'll shoot you dead!

57:29.239 --> 57:30.824
<i>Get out of here, Wentworth.</i>

57:42.252 --> 57:43.962
♪♪

57:44.170 --> 57:48.925
You can't shoot us dead,
Richard.

57:49.175 --> 57:53.304
Because we're already dead.

57:54.305 --> 57:58.017
We want to see you, Richard.

57:58.226 --> 58:02.856
- We want to see you, Richard.
- We want to see you, Richard.

58:03.189 --> 58:04.858
BECKY:
<i>We want to see you.</i>

58:05.066 --> 58:05.733
(gunshot)

58:05.942 --> 58:08.945
HARRY:
<i>We dug a hole for you, Richard.</i>

58:09.195 --> 58:10.822
BECKY:
On the beach.

58:11.072 --> 58:13.992
HARRY:
<i>Below the high-tide line.</i>

58:14.200 --> 58:14.909
(gunshot)

58:15.118 --> 58:17.829
- Here we come.
- (gunshot)

58:18.121 --> 58:20.748
It's showtime!

58:21.166 --> 58:21.916
(gunshot)

58:22.625 --> 58:26.171
- Here we come, Richard.
- Here we come.

58:26.629 --> 58:27.422
(gunshots)

58:27.630 --> 58:30.300
Let's go to the beach.

58:30.508 --> 58:34.971
- We just want you to come to the beach.
- We just want you to come to the beach.

58:35.180 --> 58:35.847
(grunting)

58:36.055 --> 58:37.724
- Come with us.
- Come with us.

58:38.141 --> 58:40.810
- Come down to the beach.
- Come down to the beach.

58:41.019 --> 58:43.104
(shouting)

58:45.315 --> 58:47.066
(panting)

59:01.956 --> 59:03.958
(screaming)

59:04.167 --> 59:07.587
If you don't panic...

59:08.379 --> 59:11.508
...if you can
hold your breath....

59:11.716 --> 59:12.383
(screaming)

59:12.592 --> 59:16.804
If you can hold your breath....

59:17.263 --> 59:19.807
(screaming)

59:20.016 --> 59:22.977
If you can hold your breath....

59:23.186 --> 59:26.731
- If you can hold your breath....
- If you can hold your breath....

59:26.940 --> 59:29.859
(laughing hysterically)

59:31.569 --> 59:33.321
(Vickers screaming)

59:38.576 --> 59:41.621
I can hold my breath...

59:42.080 --> 59:45.333
...for a long time!

59:45.542 --> 59:47.293
(laughing hysterically)

59:47.877 --> 59:49.629
(waves rumbling)

59:50.088 --> 59:51.839
♪♪

01:00:02.183 --> 01:00:03.935
(lightning crashes)

01:00:23.204 --> 01:00:24.956
(coins clattering)

01:00:28.376 --> 01:00:30.670
There, look at that.
(scoffs)

01:00:30.962 --> 01:00:31.963
Fuck-a-diddle.

01:00:40.305 --> 01:00:42.015
(rattling)

01:00:44.767 --> 01:00:46.436
MAN: <i>What the...?</i>

01:00:56.904 --> 01:00:59.282
WOMAN:
<i>Oh, Dexter, you are such a child.</i>

01:00:59.490 --> 01:01:01.784
<i>You and Henry both.
You're such children.</i>

01:01:02.660 --> 01:01:05.913
But at least Henry has me
to take care of him, don't you, dear?

01:01:06.456 --> 01:01:10.251
Tabby, Richard, I'd like you to meet
Dexter Stanley, our distinguished professor...

01:01:10.460 --> 01:01:13.421
- ...in the Zoology Department.
- Oh, how do--?

01:01:13.671 --> 01:01:16.466
Tabby and Richard Raymond.
They're new in the Math Department.

01:01:16.674 --> 01:01:18.593
How do you do?
What a lovely name you have.

01:01:18.801 --> 01:01:20.595
Oh, thank you.
Actually, it's Tabitha.

01:01:21.262 --> 01:01:22.930
It's a pleasure to meet you,
Professor Stanley.

01:01:23.181 --> 01:01:24.724
- Just Dex will do.
- Dex. Thank you.

01:01:24.974 --> 01:01:28.603
- This is Henry and Wilma Northrup.
- Oh, just call me Billie. Everyone does.

01:01:28.770 --> 01:01:31.189
- Billie.
- You need someone to show you the ropes...

01:01:31.439 --> 01:01:34.859
...you just come see me.
I know all the best stores.

01:01:35.068 --> 01:01:37.362
- Well, nice to meet you.
- Nice to meet you.

01:01:37.612 --> 01:01:39.947
- Pleasure to meet you.
- So, are you buying or renting?

01:01:40.156 --> 01:01:43.076
- Oh, actually, we're renting at the moment.
- It's just as well.

01:01:43.326 --> 01:01:46.245
Buying real estate in a college town
is a frigging pain in the ass.

01:01:46.496 --> 01:01:47.455
<i>Take my word for it.</i>

01:01:47.664 --> 01:01:50.083
Henry is in the English Department,
and Wilma--

01:01:50.375 --> 01:01:53.878
I just take care of Henry.
Believe me, he needs it.

01:01:54.087 --> 01:01:55.588
Did you ever meet
a man who didn't?

01:01:55.797 --> 01:01:56.881
(laughing)

01:01:57.090 --> 01:02:00.468
- What's the matter? You're not drinking?
- Well, actually, we just got here.

01:02:00.677 --> 01:02:02.804
Oh, well, we can
take care of that.

01:02:03.388 --> 01:02:05.848
You just come on with me.
Henry, you stay here till I get back.

01:02:06.057 --> 01:02:08.017
- Excuse us, please.
- Yeah, nice to meet you.

01:02:08.851 --> 01:02:10.353
Bye.

01:02:11.729 --> 01:02:13.231
♪♪

01:02:13.439 --> 01:02:16.109
Oh, honey, these people are dry.
Now, take care of them.

01:02:16.317 --> 01:02:17.944
They don't know
what they're doing.

01:02:21.906 --> 01:02:24.075
Hi. Good to see you.

01:02:26.494 --> 01:02:30.331
If Dex Stanley hadn't had his teeth capped,
he'd have been out on his ass years ago.

01:02:30.540 --> 01:02:31.541
Really? Well, my--

01:02:31.749 --> 01:02:34.794
So when Parker told me
that I was out of line...

01:02:35.044 --> 01:02:36.671
...I told him
he ought to get laid.

01:02:36.879 --> 01:02:37.547
(snorting)

01:02:37.755 --> 01:02:41.300
"I mean, Parker," I said,
"if you'd just have your ashes hauled...

01:02:41.509 --> 01:02:44.971
...you wouldn't have to spend all this time
playing Emily Vanderbilt."

01:02:45.179 --> 01:02:49.600
Or Emily Van Buren,
or whoever that etiquette crotch is.

01:02:49.809 --> 01:02:53.563
- Excuse me.
- I don't know why they keep inviting her.

01:02:53.855 --> 01:02:57.442
- Hello, Mrs. Forest, ladies.
- Oh, Professor Stanley.

01:03:07.118 --> 01:03:09.954
Well, how about tonight?
Maybe we could do it tonight?

01:03:11.956 --> 01:03:15.793
- Okay. That's great.
- All right, I'll call you about it.

01:03:18.171 --> 01:03:21.632
I gather you'll be unavailable
for chess tonight.

01:03:21.841 --> 01:03:22.675
(chuckling)

01:03:24.719 --> 01:03:28.347
Henry, you know, I'm just about
reaching a point where I--

01:03:28.556 --> 01:03:30.933
Pardon me. Would one of you
be Professor Stanley?

01:03:31.142 --> 01:03:33.311
- Yeah, I am.
- WOMAN: <i>There's a telephone call for you.</i>

01:03:33.519 --> 01:03:35.188
DEXTER:
<i>Oh, yeah, all right. Thank you.</i>

01:03:35.855 --> 01:03:39.567
It's probably Charlie Gereson again
with his damn ear mites.

01:03:39.776 --> 01:03:41.819
He's gonna get the Nobel Prize
before he's 20.

01:03:42.028 --> 01:03:44.405
Especially if he's working
at Amberson Hall in August.

01:03:44.655 --> 01:03:46.532
No, no, he's downstairs.
It's cooler.

01:03:50.453 --> 01:03:52.497
Yeah, sure, I'll come tonight.

01:03:52.705 --> 01:03:56.083
- HENRY: <i>Oh, thanks, Dex.</i>
- Oh, hey, listen, what are friends for?

01:03:56.459 --> 01:03:59.170
WILMA: <i>Just call me Billie.
Everyone does.</i>

01:04:05.384 --> 01:04:09.555
So I thought I ought to call you anyway,
see what you thought, Professor Stanley.

01:04:09.764 --> 01:04:13.643
- Who told you I was here? Charlie Gereson?
- JANITOR: <i>Yeah. I sent him out for a hamburger.</i>

01:04:14.435 --> 01:04:15.228
Just about twisted his arm.

01:04:15.436 --> 01:04:18.064
That kid don't know if it's night or day
when he gets going.

01:04:18.356 --> 01:04:19.982
Yeah, he's very dedicated.

01:04:20.316 --> 01:04:23.778
Look, I'd be almost willing to bet
that crate's full of <i>National Geographics...</i>

01:04:23.986 --> 01:04:25.863
<i>...or back issues of the</i> Reader's Digest.

01:04:26.113 --> 01:04:30.326
Well, the date on it said 1834.

01:04:30.743 --> 01:04:34.956
Did they publish the <i>Reader's Digest</i>
way back then, Professor Stanley?

01:04:35.206 --> 01:04:39.335
- 1834? Really?
- JANITOR: <i>Yeah, it's stenciled right on the side.</i>

01:04:39.627 --> 01:04:42.922
June 19, 1834.

01:04:43.214 --> 01:04:46.425
And then something about
an arctic expedition.

01:04:46.634 --> 01:04:48.553
Maybe there's something
more interesting in your crate

01:04:48.761 --> 01:04:50.638
than <i>National Geographics</i>
after all, Mike.

01:04:56.435 --> 01:04:58.187
(engine turning over)

01:05:00.189 --> 01:05:03.860
Because everyone in the department
is looking to put the knife in you.

01:05:04.068 --> 01:05:07.780
- I mean, some of these so-called academics--
- Wilma.

01:05:07.989 --> 01:05:10.867
--make the shark in <i>Jaws</i>
look like fucking <i>Flipper.</i>

01:05:11.117 --> 01:05:14.412
- Wilma.
- Your husband's calling you, Billie.

01:05:14.662 --> 01:05:16.789
Oh, God, Henry,
what's wrong now?

01:05:17.123 --> 01:05:18.332
(gunshot)

01:05:18.541 --> 01:05:19.792
HENRY:
<i>Not a thing, Wilma.</i>

01:05:20.001 --> 01:05:21.419
(blows barrel)

01:05:21.627 --> 01:05:23.296
Everything's just fine.

01:05:24.422 --> 01:05:26.173
♪♪

01:05:29.093 --> 01:05:30.845
(polite clapping)

01:05:38.561 --> 01:05:40.563
- Hell of a shot.
- Bull's-eye.

01:05:41.647 --> 01:05:43.691
WILMA: <i>Oh, Henry,
can't you do anything right?</i>

01:05:44.400 --> 01:05:46.360
- HENRY: <i>Huh?</i>
- "Huh?"

01:05:46.569 --> 01:05:48.696
That's what I figured. "Huh."

01:05:48.905 --> 01:05:50.823
<i>That's just what I'd
expect from you.</i>

01:05:51.032 --> 01:05:52.533
<i>I told you half an hour ago...</i>

01:05:52.742 --> 01:05:57.163
<i>...to get one of them kids in the
monkey suits to bring the car around.</i>

01:05:57.413 --> 01:05:59.081
Oh, I'm sorry.

01:05:59.290 --> 01:06:03.294
Oh, Henry, you are
such a little kid.

01:06:03.502 --> 01:06:05.588
I swear to God, you are.

01:06:05.922 --> 01:06:08.758
I mean, where would you be
without me to take care of you?

01:06:11.469 --> 01:06:13.220
♪♪

01:06:15.181 --> 01:06:21.270
DEXTER: I'm still betting your crate's
full of old magazines and just plain junk.

01:06:21.479 --> 01:06:22.438
(flashlight clicks on)

01:06:23.105 --> 01:06:24.482
DEXTER:
<i>All the same, though....</i>

01:06:24.982 --> 01:06:27.526
<i>An arctic expedition.</i>

01:06:27.735 --> 01:06:29.487
<i>And that date.</i>

01:06:29.695 --> 01:06:32.823
Yeah, kind of gets you,
doesn't it?

01:06:33.074 --> 01:06:35.326
Yeah, it kind of does.

01:06:35.534 --> 01:06:36.243
(grate banging)

01:06:36.452 --> 01:06:38.913
- I'm sorry.
- Got it.

01:06:39.121 --> 01:06:40.623
MIKE:
It's kind of heavy.

01:06:40.915 --> 01:06:43.250
I'll just swing this end around.

01:06:46.921 --> 01:06:49.757
Yeah. Move it over here.

01:06:49.966 --> 01:06:52.134
DEXTER: I'm surprised you didn't
open this thing yourself.

01:06:52.343 --> 01:06:54.512
MIKE:
<i>No, I figured that was for you.</i>

01:06:54.804 --> 01:06:56.597
DEXTER: How come you didn't tell
Charlie Gereson?

01:06:56.806 --> 01:06:58.599
Well, he's just a grad student.

01:06:58.849 --> 01:07:01.060
And with Professor Tirrell
being over in England...

01:07:01.268 --> 01:07:02.645
...I figure you're the boss.

01:07:10.444 --> 01:07:12.613
- Hold this on it, will you?
- Yeah.

01:07:16.450 --> 01:07:18.244
What made you look
under here, anyway?

01:07:18.452 --> 01:07:20.287
I flipped a quarter
trying to decide...

01:07:20.538 --> 01:07:23.916
...if I should buff the second-floor hallway
first or wash the lab windows.

01:07:24.333 --> 01:07:27.545
Only when it came down, I missed it,
and it rolled under here.

01:07:27.753 --> 01:07:29.505
♪♪

01:07:30.673 --> 01:07:32.591
MIKE: <i>Oh, there it is.</i>

01:07:34.593 --> 01:07:36.053
Probably would have let it go...

01:07:36.262 --> 01:07:38.889
...only that was my last quarter
for the Coke machine.

01:07:43.227 --> 01:07:47.606
It's not very nice in there, is it?
God, I hate tight places.

01:07:52.236 --> 01:07:54.864
- Are you okay, doc?
- Yeah.

01:08:05.624 --> 01:08:06.542
(thudding)

01:08:10.087 --> 01:08:14.425
Help me out with this, will you?
I think we might really have something here.

01:08:15.718 --> 01:08:17.720
All right. Okay?

01:08:28.354 --> 01:08:30.608
DEXTER:
Put it right on this table here.

01:08:43.953 --> 01:08:48.250
- What's wrong?
- It felt like something shifted in there.

01:08:48.834 --> 01:08:50.877
Did you feel it
when we lifted it on the table?

01:08:51.087 --> 01:08:53.589
I did feel something
under the stairs. It felt heavy.

01:08:53.839 --> 01:08:57.718
Yeah, but it seemed like
something moved on its own.

01:08:58.010 --> 01:09:01.555
Well, if there ever really were
any living specimens in there...

01:09:01.805 --> 01:09:06.310
...I doubt if they're feeling
very lively after, what, 147 years?

01:09:06.519 --> 01:09:08.395
Oh, yeah. Sure.

01:09:08.604 --> 01:09:09.479
(chuckles)

01:09:09.688 --> 01:09:12.608
I guess I must be spending too much
time in the sun, huh, doc?

01:09:12.817 --> 01:09:15.069
- Well, let's get this open, shall we?
- Yeah.

01:09:15.819 --> 01:09:19.573
I got a hammer and chisel out in the closet.
Just wait while I go get them.

01:09:19.948 --> 01:09:22.033
Yeah. Hit those lights,
will you, Mike?

01:09:29.250 --> 01:09:30.376
(sighs)

01:09:30.584 --> 01:09:33.420
And don't just leave the pots soaking
like you did last time.

01:09:33.629 --> 01:09:35.756
<i>Scrub them and put them away.</i>

01:09:35.965 --> 01:09:38.551
Just because you
and your intellectual friend...

01:09:38.759 --> 01:09:42.054
...are gonna play chess, doesn't mean
you have to leave a mess for me.

01:09:42.263 --> 01:09:43.264
(sighs)

01:09:44.598 --> 01:09:45.933
Wipe the stove.

01:09:46.809 --> 01:09:47.768
Yes, Billie.

01:09:47.977 --> 01:09:52.606
And kindly have him out of here
before I get back from my classes.

01:09:52.982 --> 01:09:56.944
But frankly, that tobacco he smokes
makes me wanna ralph.

01:09:58.779 --> 01:10:00.531
♪♪

01:10:00.739 --> 01:10:04.743
Yes, Billie. Yes.

01:10:05.452 --> 01:10:07.371
"Yes, Billie. Yes, Billie."

01:10:07.580 --> 01:10:08.622
(sighs)

01:10:08.831 --> 01:10:12.877
Oh, Henry.
What would you do without me?

01:10:13.419 --> 01:10:15.087
I don't know, Billie.

01:10:17.548 --> 01:10:20.801
Well, on that we're even.

01:10:22.428 --> 01:10:24.597
Enjoy your chess.

01:10:24.805 --> 01:10:26.557
(footsteps clicking)

01:10:28.058 --> 01:10:28.893
(lock clinking)

01:10:32.938 --> 01:10:35.608
- I bet they're worth something, huh, doc?
- Yeah.

01:10:37.443 --> 01:10:38.527
Doc.

01:10:38.777 --> 01:10:41.614
No, no. Be my guest, Mike.
It's your find.

01:10:41.822 --> 01:10:42.489
(chuckles)

01:10:42.698 --> 01:10:45.492
You're right. There's probably
nothing in there but rocks and plants...

01:10:45.743 --> 01:10:47.578
...that'll turn to dust if you touch them.

01:10:47.870 --> 01:10:50.831
- But I'm pretty hot to see, just the same.
- To tell you the truth, so am I.

01:10:51.040 --> 01:10:52.791
(clinking)

01:10:53.167 --> 01:10:56.170
Doc, it's loosening up.
Could you...?

01:10:56.378 --> 01:10:58.172
Yeah, sure.

01:10:59.423 --> 01:11:01.175
(clinking)

01:11:04.303 --> 01:11:06.055
(clinking continues)

01:11:07.640 --> 01:11:09.391
(wood creaking)

01:11:09.725 --> 01:11:10.559
(grunting)

01:11:15.147 --> 01:11:16.065
(blowing)

01:11:16.482 --> 01:11:17.274
(groaning)

01:11:17.650 --> 01:11:19.401
(hammering)

01:11:32.998 --> 01:11:34.750
(rattling)

01:11:56.522 --> 01:11:58.274
(coughing)

01:12:02.528 --> 01:12:05.447
Christ, I can't see
a frigging thing.

01:12:06.365 --> 01:12:08.742
Where did I leave my flashlight?
Do you remember, doc?

01:12:09.702 --> 01:12:12.496
Never mind. Let's just get
this last nail out of there.

01:12:12.705 --> 01:12:14.456
(chittering)

01:12:16.959 --> 01:12:18.335
MIKE:
<i>Do you hear that?</i>

01:12:18.544 --> 01:12:19.670
(chittering)

01:12:23.007 --> 01:12:24.842
There's something in there, doc.

01:12:27.219 --> 01:12:28.637
<i>There's something shiny.</i>

01:12:29.513 --> 01:12:30.723
Christ.

01:12:30.931 --> 01:12:32.641
- It looks like a couple of emeralds.
- Don't!

01:12:32.850 --> 01:12:34.601
(screaming)

01:12:35.519 --> 01:12:38.188
Help me, doc! Help me, doc!

01:12:38.397 --> 01:12:41.066
God, it's biting. Help me!

01:12:43.068 --> 01:12:46.238
(screaming)

01:12:46.739 --> 01:12:48.490
Oh, God.

01:12:52.745 --> 01:12:53.662
Mike.

01:12:55.039 --> 01:12:55.664
<i>Mike.</i>

01:13:05.966 --> 01:13:08.802
(growling)

01:13:14.266 --> 01:13:16.018
♪♪

01:13:21.732 --> 01:13:22.524
(shouting)

01:13:34.620 --> 01:13:35.704
(yelling)

01:13:39.458 --> 01:13:41.794
(screaming)

01:13:42.002 --> 01:13:44.129
(growling)

01:13:44.338 --> 01:13:45.089
(outlet sparking)

01:13:50.427 --> 01:13:51.387
(drink rattling)

01:13:52.012 --> 01:13:52.846
(doors banging)

01:13:53.055 --> 01:13:55.849
- Oh, Jesus. Charlie. Charlie!
- Professor Stanley, what--?

01:13:56.058 --> 01:13:58.268
The janitor. The crate.

01:13:58.477 --> 01:13:59.728
It was-- It was....

01:14:01.105 --> 01:14:02.523
What happened?
Professor, slow down.

01:14:02.773 --> 01:14:05.484
Charlie, listen, we gotta
get the campus security.

01:14:05.692 --> 01:14:08.946
- We gotta get the--
- Slow down, Professor Stanley, slow down.

01:14:09.196 --> 01:14:11.740
I don't know what
you're talking about.

01:14:11.949 --> 01:14:16.453
Charlie, it's the-- You know the janitor?
You know Mike, the janitor?

01:14:16.745 --> 01:14:19.957
- Yes, of course I do.
- Well....

01:14:20.290 --> 01:14:22.042
♪♪

01:14:23.585 --> 01:14:25.963
(scraping)

01:14:27.005 --> 01:14:28.757
(growling)

01:14:34.888 --> 01:14:36.640
(scraping continues)

01:14:38.517 --> 01:14:40.269
(growling)

01:14:49.027 --> 01:14:51.780
It just sucked him in.

01:14:53.407 --> 01:14:58.328
- That's pretty far out, Professor Stanley.
- It's true, it's true. I swear to God, it's true.

01:14:58.620 --> 01:15:02.624
- Come on, we gotta get the campus police.
- No, campus security's no good.

01:15:04.585 --> 01:15:07.337
If I'm having trouble swallowing this,
what the fuck are they going to think?

01:15:07.546 --> 01:15:09.298
I don't know
what they would think.

01:15:12.342 --> 01:15:14.636
I don't know
what they would think.

01:15:14.887 --> 01:15:17.931
They'd think you'd been off
on a hell of a toot.

01:15:18.807 --> 01:15:21.226
- But, Charlie....
- No, no.

01:15:21.477 --> 01:15:24.146
They'd think we'd both been off
on a hell of a toot.

01:15:24.354 --> 01:15:27.983
Got you seeing Tasmanian devils
instead of pink elephants.

01:15:28.192 --> 01:15:31.445
I think I'll go down...

01:15:32.154 --> 01:15:33.864
...and see how the land lays.

01:15:34.072 --> 01:15:38.035
- No, don't! It may be out.
- No, I doubt that.

01:15:38.285 --> 01:15:42.039
- Charlie, please don't go down there.
- CHARLIE: <i>Be right back, Professor Stanley.</i>

01:15:46.835 --> 01:15:47.961
He'll see it.

01:15:48.545 --> 01:15:52.466
He'll see the crate, he'll see the blood,
he'll see Mike, and then he'll believe me.

01:15:57.304 --> 01:15:58.430
<i>Charlie.</i>

01:16:00.807 --> 01:16:01.767
Charlie?

01:16:08.815 --> 01:16:12.110
There, see the blood?
Do you think I'm crazy now?

01:16:17.449 --> 01:16:20.911
You think that I killed him?
Look at the blood. Look--

01:16:22.829 --> 01:16:23.539
It's gone.

01:16:24.081 --> 01:16:26.333
- What's gone?
- The....

01:16:30.045 --> 01:16:31.588
It got out.

01:16:32.297 --> 01:16:35.509
I thought it would be potbound
after all these years, but it got out.

01:16:35.717 --> 01:16:39.846
It pushed the crate off the table.
From the way this track looks....

01:16:46.103 --> 01:16:48.355
It pushed the crate back in
under the stairs...

01:16:49.356 --> 01:16:51.191
...where it felt safe
for so long.

01:16:53.986 --> 01:16:55.529
Hey, Charlie.

01:17:02.744 --> 01:17:04.079
Charlie, I really think--

01:17:10.210 --> 01:17:11.962
♪♪

01:17:12.296 --> 01:17:13.213
(flashlight clicks on)

01:17:29.146 --> 01:17:30.897
(clattering)

01:17:38.322 --> 01:17:41.450
Charlie, listen, don't go in there.
If you had seen that thing....

01:17:41.700 --> 01:17:42.743
Don't worry.

01:17:45.245 --> 01:17:46.830
Christ.

01:17:54.254 --> 01:17:56.298
<i>It looks like it's been through
a hay baler.</i>

01:17:56.965 --> 01:17:58.383
Now do you believe me?

01:18:01.053 --> 01:18:02.512
Charlie, don't go near it.

01:18:03.305 --> 01:18:04.640
I don't want the crate...

01:18:06.516 --> 01:18:07.976
...I want that shoe.

01:18:09.061 --> 01:18:10.896
<i>I wanna measure the bite marks.</i>

01:18:13.565 --> 01:18:14.816
Maybe we can figure out...

01:18:16.526 --> 01:18:18.612
...what we're dealing with here.

01:18:20.072 --> 01:18:20.989
(shuddering)

01:18:27.245 --> 01:18:28.997
♪♪

01:18:35.337 --> 01:18:36.963
(growling)

01:18:37.172 --> 01:18:37.923
(screaming)

01:18:41.468 --> 01:18:42.469
(ripping)

01:18:42.678 --> 01:18:43.845
(yelling)

01:18:44.262 --> 01:18:45.806
(roaring)

01:18:50.477 --> 01:18:52.229
- (thudding)
- (roaring)

01:19:00.278 --> 01:19:01.113
(growling)

01:19:03.490 --> 01:19:04.866
No, Charlie!

01:19:05.075 --> 01:19:06.827
(screaming)

01:19:10.789 --> 01:19:12.541
(screaming)

01:19:20.549 --> 01:19:21.883
We gotta--

01:19:22.092 --> 01:19:25.095
We gotta stop it.
We gotta stop it.

01:19:25.303 --> 01:19:26.888
- What?
- Two people are dead already.

01:19:27.097 --> 01:19:30.642
We gotta--
Dear Christ, they died.

01:19:30.851 --> 01:19:33.478
Hey, Dex. Dex, hold it.

01:19:33.687 --> 01:19:34.730
(door closing)

01:19:35.772 --> 01:19:38.358
- What happened?
- Two people are dead already.

01:19:38.900 --> 01:19:41.278
- And....
- Who's dead?

01:19:43.029 --> 01:19:45.699
- Where's Wilma?
- She's gone. Dex, what the--?

01:19:45.907 --> 01:19:47.325
What the hell happened to you?

01:19:47.534 --> 01:19:50.996
Two people are dead,
and I could be blamed.

01:19:51.246 --> 01:19:55.125
I know that's a terrible consideration
to have at a time like this, Henry....

01:19:57.669 --> 01:19:58.920
(gulping)

01:19:59.129 --> 01:20:00.672
HENRY:
<i>Good God.</i>

01:20:01.631 --> 01:20:04.634
Last time I saw someone do that
was in the movies.

01:20:04.801 --> 01:20:07.012
DEXTER: <i>It could be my ass,
Henry, and it wasn't me.</i>

01:20:07.304 --> 01:20:10.932
It was that thing in the--
in the crate.

01:20:11.141 --> 01:20:14.144
I don't even know what it was.

01:20:14.352 --> 01:20:16.730
What two people? Who is dead?

01:20:20.984 --> 01:20:23.403
Mike, the janitor
in Amberson Hall...

01:20:24.237 --> 01:20:25.989
...and Charlie Gereson.

01:20:26.448 --> 01:20:28.909
He wanted to measure
the bite marks, Henry.

01:20:29.117 --> 01:20:30.160
(laughing)

01:20:30.368 --> 01:20:32.245
I guess he got his chance.

01:20:32.662 --> 01:20:34.581
- I certainly guess he did.
- Dex, Dex.

01:20:34.790 --> 01:20:36.708
Dex, I can't do
anything for you...

01:20:36.958 --> 01:20:39.336
...unless you stop being
so goddamned elliptical.

01:20:39.544 --> 01:20:43.381
Now, just slow down.
Tell me the whole story from the beginning.

01:20:43.590 --> 01:20:46.051
- Can you do that?
- All right. All right.

01:20:46.259 --> 01:20:47.886
I think I can do that now.

01:20:48.094 --> 01:20:50.013
Oh, thank God for you, Henry.

01:20:50.222 --> 01:20:51.848
♪♪

01:20:56.186 --> 01:20:59.564
I had a hundred crazy ideas
about how to get rid of it coming over here.

01:20:59.856 --> 01:21:01.441
I kept thinking about Ryder's Quarry.

01:21:01.650 --> 01:21:03.109
- You know that place?
- I know it.

01:21:03.318 --> 01:21:05.195
I kept thinking
that would be deep enough...

01:21:05.487 --> 01:21:08.114
...if only there was a way
to get that crate over there.

01:21:08.323 --> 01:21:10.826
You know, I kept
thinking if we....

01:21:11.034 --> 01:21:12.118
(scoffs)

01:21:12.702 --> 01:21:14.454
I don't know anymore.

01:21:17.707 --> 01:21:19.334
Am I going crazy, Henry?

01:21:20.043 --> 01:21:20.877
No.

01:21:24.381 --> 01:21:28.510
I have to use
the facilities, Dex.

01:21:28.718 --> 01:21:30.136
I'll be back in a minute.

01:21:31.179 --> 01:21:35.016
And then we'll decide
what we need to do.

01:21:35.225 --> 01:21:39.062
- Thanks, Henry.
- Well, what are friends for?

01:21:40.564 --> 01:21:41.356
(sighs)

01:21:45.569 --> 01:21:48.071
(pills rattling)

01:21:49.406 --> 01:21:52.951
- Let's get you another drink, Dex.
- No, no, no, I've had enough.

01:21:53.201 --> 01:21:56.121
It's a wonder I'm not
plastered out of my gourd.

01:21:56.496 --> 01:21:57.789
<i>Shock, I guess.</i>

01:21:58.123 --> 01:22:01.418
Just one more for the both of us
while we talk this over.

01:22:02.419 --> 01:22:05.422
- We may need it.
- Yeah, okay.

01:22:09.801 --> 01:22:11.553
(clock ticking)

01:22:14.347 --> 01:22:17.309
♪♪

01:22:22.814 --> 01:22:24.566
(door closes, locks)

01:22:35.660 --> 01:22:37.412
(engine revving)

01:22:44.669 --> 01:22:47.631
(engine stops,
emergency brake ratchets)

01:22:50.508 --> 01:22:51.384
(car door shuts)

01:22:58.642 --> 01:23:00.936
My God.

01:23:24.542 --> 01:23:25.335
(clattering)

01:23:51.653 --> 01:23:53.363
(flashlight rattling)

01:24:08.920 --> 01:24:10.672
♪♪

01:24:15.135 --> 01:24:16.886
(tap squeaking,
water running)

01:24:30.942 --> 01:24:32.694
(emergency brake ratcheting)

01:24:37.615 --> 01:24:38.450
(car door closes)

01:24:40.827 --> 01:24:42.579
♪♪

01:24:52.547 --> 01:24:54.299
(keys rattling)

01:24:55.508 --> 01:24:57.469
Henry, goddamn it!

01:24:57.719 --> 01:25:01.306
How many times have I told you
to lock the goddamn door?

01:25:03.850 --> 01:25:04.851
Henry.

01:25:06.519 --> 01:25:08.271
(water sloshing)

01:25:11.816 --> 01:25:12.776
WILMA: <i>Henry!</i>

01:25:18.948 --> 01:25:19.908
(mop slapping)

01:25:26.748 --> 01:25:32.462
HENRY: <i>Wilma, I've had to leave in a hurry
because of a call from Dexter Stanley.</i>

01:25:32.670 --> 01:25:36.091
<i>He seems to have gotten himself
in a great deal of trouble.</i>

01:25:36.633 --> 01:25:41.096
<i>I'm ashamed to tell you of this,
but ever since Dexter's wife died...</i>

01:25:41.387 --> 01:25:45.850
<i>...he's had problems coping with
certain young female grad students.</i>

01:25:46.059 --> 01:25:48.186
<i>He's been able to cover up
several incidents...</i>

01:25:48.478 --> 01:25:51.064
<i>...but this one looks
very serious.</i>

01:25:55.443 --> 01:25:59.322
<i>It seems he got a young woman
to accompany him to Amberson Hall...</i>

01:25:59.531 --> 01:26:01.866
...under false pretenses
and then attacked her.

01:26:05.995 --> 01:26:08.623
<i>When Dex called me,
he was barely coherent.</i>

01:26:08.873 --> 01:26:12.293
<i>He was gibbering with fear
and crying, I think.</i>

01:26:12.502 --> 01:26:14.546
Aw. Poor Dex.

01:26:14.754 --> 01:26:17.298
HENRY: <i>I tried to get him to tell me
what had happened to the girl...</i>

01:26:17.507 --> 01:26:19.759
<i>...but for the most part,
he only kept repeating:</i>

01:26:20.009 --> 01:26:22.220
<i>"It's awful, Henry. It's awful."</i>

01:26:23.263 --> 01:26:25.640
<i>Wilma, could you come out here?</i>

01:26:26.516 --> 01:26:28.059
<i>I know it's asking a lot...</i>

01:26:28.351 --> 01:26:31.229
<i>...but you're always so clear-headed
about these things...</i>

01:26:31.437 --> 01:26:33.064
<i>...and you know how to be firm.</i>

01:26:34.399 --> 01:26:38.069
<i>I think Dex could use a firmer hand
than mine right now.</i>

01:26:38.653 --> 01:26:40.780
<i>Not to mention the girl herself.</i>

01:26:41.322 --> 01:26:46.244
<i>He said that she had curled up
in a dark place and won't come out.</i>

01:26:46.786 --> 01:26:51.791
<i>I'm sorry to have to ask you to come over
to Amberson Hall and help me out...</i>

01:26:52.000 --> 01:26:56.337
<i>...but as you so often say,
what would I do without you?</i>

01:26:56.546 --> 01:26:59.757
What indeed, Henry? What indeed?

01:26:59.966 --> 01:27:01.718
(laughing)

01:27:05.471 --> 01:27:06.764
(laughing)

01:27:06.973 --> 01:27:08.183
(horn honking)

01:27:11.311 --> 01:27:13.897
(mop slapping)

01:27:53.561 --> 01:27:55.063
♪♪

01:27:55.271 --> 01:27:56.272
(door closing)

01:28:02.445 --> 01:28:04.197
(bucket rattling)

01:28:08.826 --> 01:28:10.161
WILMA:
Henry?

01:28:18.086 --> 01:28:19.337
<i>Henry?</i>

01:28:23.841 --> 01:28:25.468
Henry, where are you?

01:28:26.552 --> 01:28:28.096
HENRY:
<i>The laboratory, Wilma.</i>

01:28:28.846 --> 01:28:30.265
<i>Downstairs.</i>

01:28:30.473 --> 01:28:31.557
(sighs)

01:28:38.690 --> 01:28:40.108
(clattering)

01:28:44.112 --> 01:28:45.863
(door closes)

01:28:46.281 --> 01:28:48.032
(footsteps)

01:28:56.833 --> 01:28:59.127
What are you doing
creeping around down there?

01:29:00.837 --> 01:29:02.505
Where's Dex?

01:29:02.714 --> 01:29:05.800
What kind of a mess
has he gotten himself into?

01:29:06.009 --> 01:29:11.055
Well, it's easier if I just show
you, I think. Come on down.

01:29:14.225 --> 01:29:18.479
- What's this?
- Oh, I found them in the....

01:29:18.688 --> 01:29:20.315
Oh, Henry.

01:29:21.482 --> 01:29:22.692
Did he beat her?

01:29:23.693 --> 01:29:24.902
Well....

01:29:25.445 --> 01:29:28.573
Well, how bad is she?
Is she conscious?

01:29:30.825 --> 01:29:31.909
(sniffling)

01:29:38.624 --> 01:29:42.587
HENRY: I think it's easier if you
just see for yourself, Wilma.

01:29:42.795 --> 01:29:44.339
(chuckling)

01:29:45.048 --> 01:29:46.382
What are you laughing about?

01:29:46.591 --> 01:29:48.176
(laughing)

01:29:48.593 --> 01:29:51.137
Your best friend gets in a scrape
with a girl and you're laughing?

01:29:51.346 --> 01:29:52.055
(laughing)

01:29:52.263 --> 01:29:55.183
Well, there is a
funny side to it, Wilma.

01:29:55.391 --> 01:29:58.102
Wait till you see.
You'll think so yourself.

01:29:58.311 --> 01:29:59.395
(laughing)

01:29:59.604 --> 01:30:03.691
You're hysterical, Henry.
It's just what I would have expected.

01:30:05.234 --> 01:30:08.279
No, I don't think
you'll expect this, Wilma.

01:30:09.322 --> 01:30:13.117
No, this is going to be
an entirely new experience.

01:30:13.743 --> 01:30:17.246
What are you doing, Henry?
Let go of me. Henry.

01:30:18.164 --> 01:30:21.542
What's going on?
The lab's the other way.

01:30:21.751 --> 01:30:27.048
The lab, yes, but the girl
is under the stairs, Billie.

01:30:28.758 --> 01:30:30.968
Wait till you see.
That's what's so funny.

01:30:31.594 --> 01:30:35.932
The girl has crawled under the stairs,
and she won't come out.

01:30:36.140 --> 01:30:38.851
She's all curled up,
you know, like a little baby.

01:30:39.060 --> 01:30:42.063
- Oh, Henry.
- And making funny sounds and....

01:30:42.271 --> 01:30:43.773
What did he do to her?

01:30:44.649 --> 01:30:45.483
Well....

01:30:49.028 --> 01:30:50.947
You can get her out, Billie.

01:30:51.322 --> 01:30:52.740
I know you can get her out.

01:30:53.491 --> 01:30:55.952
Why don't you give it a try?

01:30:57.120 --> 01:31:01.791
You always know how to handle
these things, Billie, no problem.

01:31:02.625 --> 01:31:03.709
<i>No trouble.</i>

01:31:04.794 --> 01:31:06.379
I know you can get her out.

01:31:06.587 --> 01:31:08.339
♪♪

01:31:09.215 --> 01:31:11.217
What are you doing, Henry?
What are you doing?

01:31:11.467 --> 01:31:15.763
What I should have done a long time ago.
Get in there, Wilma!

01:31:16.347 --> 01:31:18.224
Just tell it to call you Billie,
you bitch!

01:31:18.433 --> 01:31:20.852
Stop it. Stop it, Henry.
I'll scream.

01:31:21.060 --> 01:31:24.522
Oh, scream all you want.
I'll help you. Wake up!

01:31:24.730 --> 01:31:28.860
Wake up, whatever you are.
Wake up, wake up! Dinnertime!

01:31:29.068 --> 01:31:34.907
Poison meat!
Wake up! Wake up! Wake up!

01:31:35.533 --> 01:31:39.787
Wake up. Wake up. Wake....

01:31:48.838 --> 01:31:52.675
Well, that was great, Henry.
That was just great.

01:31:53.050 --> 01:31:54.927
You think this is a
Friday-night fight?

01:31:55.261 --> 01:31:56.804
- Huh?
- (scoffs)

01:31:57.013 --> 01:31:57.847
Is that what you think?

01:31:59.265 --> 01:32:01.184
You wanna see
some real punching?

01:32:01.684 --> 01:32:03.144
(groaning)

01:32:07.773 --> 01:32:11.068
Same old Henry,
afraid of your own shadow.

01:32:12.320 --> 01:32:16.199
<i>You know what, Henry?
You're a regular barnyard exhibit.</i>

01:32:16.532 --> 01:32:21.078
Sheep's eyes, chicken guts,
piggy friends...

01:32:21.787 --> 01:32:23.748
...and shit for brains.

01:32:24.499 --> 01:32:28.961
<i>No good at departmental politics,
no good at making money...</i>

01:32:29.170 --> 01:32:31.714
<i>...no good at making an impression
on anybody.</i>

01:32:33.549 --> 01:32:36.302
And no good at all in bed.

01:32:37.094 --> 01:32:39.764
When was the last time
you got it up, Henry, huh?

01:32:40.348 --> 01:32:43.142
<i>When was the last time
you were a man in our bed?</i>

01:32:43.768 --> 01:32:45.228
Now, get out of my way, Henry...

01:32:45.436 --> 01:32:48.147
...or I swear to God you'll be
wearing your balls for earrings.

01:32:48.397 --> 01:32:50.691
And I swear to God,
if you ever touch me again--

01:32:50.900 --> 01:32:51.776
♪♪

01:32:51.984 --> 01:32:53.736
(roaring)

01:32:53.945 --> 01:32:55.696
(screaming)

01:33:01.077 --> 01:33:04.956
Oh, just-- Just tell it
to call you Billie.

01:33:11.045 --> 01:33:14.632
(gagging and retching)

01:33:29.855 --> 01:33:32.984
(lock rattling)

01:33:38.573 --> 01:33:39.448
(lock clicks open)

01:33:43.536 --> 01:33:45.288
(footsteps)

01:33:50.418 --> 01:33:51.377
(lock clicking)

01:34:10.187 --> 01:34:11.939
(chain squishing)

01:34:21.365 --> 01:34:22.408
(chain rattling)

01:34:35.338 --> 01:34:37.965
- (clattering)
- (roaring)

01:34:38.174 --> 01:34:39.925
(chain rattling)

01:34:41.010 --> 01:34:46.807
- (roaring)
- (chain rattling)

01:34:50.311 --> 01:34:51.646
(roaring)

01:34:53.022 --> 01:34:54.774
- (lock clicking shut)
- (roaring)

01:34:55.566 --> 01:34:58.778
- (chain rattling)
- (roaring)

01:34:58.986 --> 01:35:00.738
♪♪

01:35:02.615 --> 01:35:04.784
HENRY:
<i>I didn't see anyone, not a soul.</i>

01:35:05.201 --> 01:35:09.705
<i>At this time of the year and no other,
the campus is almost totally deserted.</i>

01:35:09.914 --> 01:35:13.709
<i>The summer session is over, and the fall
semester doesn't start for two more weeks.</i>

01:35:13.918 --> 01:35:16.003
<i>It was almost hellishly perfect.</i>

01:35:16.212 --> 01:35:18.589
<i>I never saw so much
as a pair of headlights.</i>

01:35:18.839 --> 01:35:22.218
<i>"Henry, what did you do
with the crate? The crate?"</i>

01:35:22.426 --> 01:35:24.053
<i>That's the beauty of it.</i>

01:35:24.428 --> 01:35:27.556
<i>You provided the final piece
in the jigsaw puzzle yourself.</i>

01:35:27.765 --> 01:35:30.685
<i>The crate is at the bottom
of Ryder's Quarry.</i>

01:35:30.935 --> 01:35:34.021
<i>I drove out there with the remains
of three human beings.</i>

01:35:34.271 --> 01:35:36.399
<i>Well, two human beings
and Wilma.</i>

01:35:37.400 --> 01:35:39.944
<i>I began to wonder,
where did they go?</i>

01:35:40.361 --> 01:35:42.613
<i>I mean, how much could it eat?</i>

01:35:42.822 --> 01:35:44.073
(growling)

01:35:44.281 --> 01:35:47.201
HENRY:
<i>I think maybe at the very end...</i>

01:35:47.410 --> 01:35:49.954
<i>...it began to suspect
what was happening.</i>

01:35:52.248 --> 01:35:53.416
(growling)

01:36:06.846 --> 01:36:08.055
(roaring)

01:36:18.190 --> 01:36:19.942
(splashing)

01:36:28.367 --> 01:36:32.288
So, the question is,
what happens now?

01:36:34.582 --> 01:36:37.668
There's no evidence of
foul play, I've seen to that.

01:36:39.503 --> 01:36:41.130
And there are no bodies.

01:36:42.757 --> 01:36:43.632
No.

01:36:44.175 --> 01:36:46.010
No, I don't suppose there are.

01:36:48.846 --> 01:36:50.806
So, what about you, Dexter?

01:36:51.724 --> 01:36:53.225
What are you gonna say?

01:36:57.396 --> 01:36:58.355
Nothing.

01:36:58.939 --> 01:36:59.565
(sighs)

01:36:59.774 --> 01:37:02.568
Thanks. Thank you, Dexter.

01:37:04.069 --> 01:37:05.780
No need to thank me.

01:37:06.405 --> 01:37:09.575
After all, what are friends for?

01:37:12.328 --> 01:37:15.664
You understand, of course,
that I expect to whip your ass at chess...

01:37:15.998 --> 01:37:18.584
<i>...twice a week
for the rest of our lives.</i>

01:37:19.210 --> 01:37:22.254
We'll have to see about that,
won't we?

01:37:26.592 --> 01:37:28.010
(sighs)

01:37:31.764 --> 01:37:33.974
I haven't done
anything to anybody.

01:37:36.227 --> 01:37:37.478
Neither have I.

01:37:40.105 --> 01:37:43.275
What if I had waked up before
you got here and called the police?

01:37:45.444 --> 01:37:46.904
You didn't.

01:37:50.574 --> 01:37:52.660
What if it gets out, Henry?

01:37:53.911 --> 01:37:55.579
What if it gets out
of that crate?

01:37:55.788 --> 01:37:56.914
(scoffs)

01:37:57.998 --> 01:38:00.960
If you saw the way I chained it up,
you wouldn't worry.

01:38:01.168 --> 01:38:04.797
<i>That thing is drowned in its box
70 feet down.</i>

01:38:05.673 --> 01:38:08.384
So, relax.

01:38:10.261 --> 01:38:11.887
Relax.

01:38:14.223 --> 01:38:16.892
♪♪

01:38:17.476 --> 01:38:19.186
(water sloshing)

01:38:21.647 --> 01:38:23.399
(wood shattering)

01:38:40.583 --> 01:38:41.375
(lightning crashes)

01:38:53.053 --> 01:38:55.764
(hissing)

01:38:56.682 --> 01:38:58.434
♪♪

01:39:17.912 --> 01:39:19.204
(whirring)

01:39:20.873 --> 01:39:22.166
(thunder rolling)

01:39:23.000 --> 01:39:24.126
Bastards.

01:39:25.002 --> 01:39:26.962
- (lightning crashes)
- (water running)

01:39:27.630 --> 01:39:29.590
Goddamn bugs.

01:39:30.215 --> 01:39:31.800
I'll get them bugs.

01:39:32.801 --> 01:39:34.511
I own this goddamn building.

01:39:34.762 --> 01:39:37.723
There's not going to be
any more damn bugs!

01:39:40.768 --> 01:39:43.771
(chittering)

01:39:45.439 --> 01:39:49.401
(phone beeping)

01:39:50.903 --> 01:39:54.198
Heads are going to roll,
I promise you that.

01:39:54.823 --> 01:39:55.950
<i>- Oh, yes.</i>
- (thunder rolling)

01:40:03.332 --> 01:40:05.668
- Hello, is that you, White?
- MAN: <i>No, sir, Mr. Pratt.</i>

01:40:05.876 --> 01:40:09.004
<i>This is George Gendron here.
I just got off the plane from Seattle.</i>

01:40:09.213 --> 01:40:10.923
<i>I have my report
ready for typing and I--</i>

01:40:11.131 --> 01:40:14.093
The building superintendent
is on vacation, George.

01:40:14.343 --> 01:40:16.637
- GEORGE: <i>Sir?</i>
- You believe that? Vacation.

01:40:16.845 --> 01:40:19.098
- GEORGE: <i>Well, I--</i>
- I told them I wanted to hear from him...

01:40:19.348 --> 01:40:22.601
...within the hour. Within the hour.
And he now has--

01:40:22.810 --> 01:40:25.521
COMPUTERIZED VOICE:
<i>It's 9:34 p.m.</i>

01:40:25.729 --> 01:40:27.564
--exactly 26 minutes to go...

01:40:27.773 --> 01:40:31.276
...or he can stay on vacation
permanently. Bastard.

01:40:31.485 --> 01:40:34.697
GEORGE: <i>Mr. Pratt, I got to the office here
and found a telex from Seattle...</i>

01:40:34.905 --> 01:40:35.906
<i>...I thought you'd want to--</i>

01:40:36.156 --> 01:40:38.909
What are you doing in the office
at 9:30, George?

01:40:39.118 --> 01:40:41.829
There's no overtime at
the executive level, you know.

01:40:42.037 --> 01:40:44.665
GEORGE: <i>Yes, I know that.
It's about the Pacific Aerodyne takeover.</i>

01:40:44.873 --> 01:40:47.543
Bugger Pacific Aerodyne.
They're done for. They've had it.

01:40:47.751 --> 01:40:49.420
Norman Castonmeyer is a dinosaur.

01:40:49.628 --> 01:40:52.589
He's too fucking blind to find his way
into the nearest tar pit.

01:40:52.798 --> 01:40:53.882
GEORGE:
<i>But, Mr. Pratt--</i>

01:40:54.091 --> 01:40:56.593
PRATT: <i>Air-pollution count's
up to almost 7, George.</i>

01:40:57.594 --> 01:41:01.265
People are dying of carbon-monoxide
poisoning, and they don't even know it.

01:41:01.473 --> 01:41:02.516
GEORGE:
<i>Yes, sir, but--</i>

01:41:02.725 --> 01:41:04.727
Oh, I found another cockroach
this evening, George.

01:41:04.935 --> 01:41:06.729
- GEORGE: <i>Oh, no.</i>
- One of those big ones...

01:41:06.937 --> 01:41:10.149
...right here in my $3200-a-month
penthouse apartment.

01:41:10.357 --> 01:41:12.943
My supposedly germ-proof apartment.

01:41:13.152 --> 01:41:16.739
Now, would you like to tell me, George,
how an apartment can be germ-proof...

01:41:16.947 --> 01:41:20.784
...when it's not even bug-proof?

01:41:21.368 --> 01:41:24.747
GEORGE: <i>Well, I guess it can't,
Mr. Pratt. But I wanted you to know...</i>

01:41:25.122 --> 01:41:29.126
<i>...that Pratt International now owns
a majority of Pacific Aerodyne's stock.</i>

01:41:29.334 --> 01:41:32.171
Of course we do.
I can't talk to you now, George.

01:41:32.379 --> 01:41:36.508
I'm gonna clear up this damn cockroach
problem once and for all. Bastards.

01:41:36.717 --> 01:41:38.469
(computer beeping)

01:41:47.227 --> 01:41:49.146
I'm not gonna have any bugs
in my building.

01:41:50.314 --> 01:41:51.857
I loathe bugs.

01:41:52.066 --> 01:41:53.942
- GEORGE: <i>Yes, sir, but, Mr.--</i>
- Loathe them.

01:41:54.234 --> 01:41:55.944
GEORGE: <i>I realize that. But there's
something you should know--</i>

01:41:56.153 --> 01:41:59.782
I've gotta let you go, George.
You did well.

01:42:00.115 --> 01:42:02.284
Go out and fuck somebody.
But wear a damn rubber.

01:42:02.493 --> 01:42:04.328
Everybody's got the damn herpes
these days.

01:42:04.578 --> 01:42:07.623
GEORGE: <i>Sir, Norman Castonmeyer
shot himself an hour ago.</i>

01:42:07.831 --> 01:42:09.583
(lightning crashes)

01:42:11.210 --> 01:42:14.004
- What?
- GEORGE: <i>He did it when....</i>

01:42:14.213 --> 01:42:18.467
<i>Well, when it became clear
there was no way to stop the takeover.</i>

01:42:18.675 --> 01:42:22.346
<i>At least, that's what
his wife thinks.</i>

01:42:23.722 --> 01:42:25.057
Wonderful.

01:42:26.058 --> 01:42:29.311
Now we won't have to offer the old fart
a seat on the board of directors.

01:42:29.561 --> 01:42:30.687
- GEORGE: <i>Yeah.</i>
- (whirring)

01:42:31.021 --> 01:42:35.400
Now, get off the phone, George.
Never run good news into the ground.

01:42:36.193 --> 01:42:38.237
I've got this bug problem.

01:42:40.030 --> 01:42:43.200
Once you get bugs,
you never get rid of them.

01:42:43.408 --> 01:42:48.122
They breed in the crawl spaces,
in the conduits...

01:42:49.123 --> 01:42:52.126
...in the very core
of the building itself.

01:42:53.252 --> 01:42:54.628
(cockroach crawling)

01:42:54.920 --> 01:42:57.965
GEORGE:
<i>Mr. Pratt? Mr. Pratt?</i>

01:42:59.675 --> 01:43:01.218
Goodbye, George.

01:43:01.927 --> 01:43:04.555
GEORGE:
<i>Yes, sir. Good night, Mr. Pratt.</i>

01:43:05.556 --> 01:43:07.349
(phone disconnects)

01:43:18.986 --> 01:43:20.195
(whirring)

01:43:21.363 --> 01:43:26.201
- (hissing)
- (whirring)

01:43:28.787 --> 01:43:31.915
Once they get a foothold in the building,
you never get rid of them.

01:43:32.207 --> 01:43:33.876
(lightning crashes)

01:43:38.255 --> 01:43:40.174
♪♪

01:43:46.305 --> 01:43:50.100
(hissing)

01:43:50.434 --> 01:43:51.602
Bastards.

01:43:52.269 --> 01:43:54.021
(phone beeping)

01:43:55.856 --> 01:43:57.482
Reynolds? White?

01:43:58.734 --> 01:43:59.943
Talk to me.

01:44:00.319 --> 01:44:04.948
WOMAN: <i>I just called to tell you
what a monster you are, Mr. Pratt...</i>

01:44:05.324 --> 01:44:09.203
<i>...and how I will rejoice
when you're finally dead.</i>

01:44:09.411 --> 01:44:12.331
Lots of people are gonna rejoice
when I'm dead.

01:44:12.664 --> 01:44:16.543
- Who are you?
- WOMAN: <i>Lenora Castonmeyer.</i>

01:44:17.586 --> 01:44:21.298
<i>I'm the wife of the man
you murdered this afternoon.</i>

01:44:21.506 --> 01:44:23.967
Mrs. Castonmeyer. How are you?

01:44:24.176 --> 01:44:27.846
LENORA: <i>I hope they keep hell
hot for you, you son of a bitch...</i>

01:44:28.055 --> 01:44:29.264
<i>...I hope they do.</i>

01:44:29.473 --> 01:44:32.226
<i>It wasn't enough for you
to drive him to his knees, was it?</i>

01:44:32.476 --> 01:44:34.394
<i>No, you had to kill him as well.</i>

01:44:34.603 --> 01:44:38.273
<i>He came home, and his eyes....</i>

01:44:38.732 --> 01:44:40.943
<i>His eyes were so dead.</i>

01:44:41.318 --> 01:44:43.153
<i>I asked him what was wrong.</i>

01:44:43.612 --> 01:44:48.200
<i>What could be so bad
to make his eyes look that way?</i>

01:44:48.408 --> 01:44:49.284
♪♪

01:44:49.493 --> 01:44:54.122
<i>And the only word he could say
was your name.</i>

01:44:54.748 --> 01:44:58.585
<i>Ten minutes later,
I heard the shot.</i>

01:44:58.794 --> 01:45:02.881
Yes, George Gendron told me
old Norman went out with a bang.

01:45:03.090 --> 01:45:05.175
LENORA:
<i>How many men have you destroyed?</i>

01:45:05.509 --> 01:45:07.594
<i>How many men have you killed,
you monster?</i>

01:45:07.928 --> 01:45:09.471
Only the stupid ones.

01:45:09.680 --> 01:45:13.684
Only the ones who handed me a knife
and then stretched out their throats.

01:45:13.892 --> 01:45:18.063
Only the ones who, if you'll
pardon the expression, fucked up.

01:45:18.272 --> 01:45:19.356
(crying)

01:45:20.023 --> 01:45:20.732
(whirring)

01:45:20.941 --> 01:45:22.985
Now, if you'll excuse me,
I've got this bug problem...

01:45:23.277 --> 01:45:26.905
...so we'll have to defer your charming
conversation for another time.

01:45:27.114 --> 01:45:29.533
- LENORA: <i>I hope you die!</i>
- By the way--

01:45:29.741 --> 01:45:32.202
LENORA: <i>I hope you get
cancer in the worst place.</i>

01:45:32.411 --> 01:45:34.788
- Mrs. Castonmeyer--
- LENORA: <i>Leprosy.</i>

01:45:35.205 --> 01:45:37.916
<i>- Scream in hell forever, you monster.</i>
- Mrs. Katzenjammer...

01:45:38.083 --> 01:45:40.794
...would you mind telling me
who gave you my private number?

01:45:41.003 --> 01:45:41.962
I'd like to fire him.

01:45:42.170 --> 01:45:44.673
LENORA: <i>It was in my husband's
address book, you son of a bitch.</i>

01:45:44.881 --> 01:45:45.966
(scoffs)

01:45:46.174 --> 01:45:48.260
Well, I can't fire him, can I?

01:45:48.802 --> 01:45:50.554
(line disconnects)

01:45:50.887 --> 01:45:52.639
(computer warbling and beeping)

01:45:54.057 --> 01:45:55.809
- (whirring)
- (chittering)

01:46:01.565 --> 01:46:02.482
(phone beeping)

01:46:02.691 --> 01:46:04.318
That better be you, Reynolds.

01:46:09.740 --> 01:46:11.742
<i>- Talk to me.</i>
MAN: <i>It's Carl Reynolds, sir.</i>

01:46:11.950 --> 01:46:15.954
<i>- I'm calling from Orlando, Florida.</i>
- Orlando? Florida?

01:46:16.204 --> 01:46:19.583
CARL: <i>Yes, the wife and I decided to
take the kids to Disney World this year--</i>

01:46:19.791 --> 01:46:22.669
I don't give a fuck if you decided
to take the kids to Attica this year.

01:46:22.961 --> 01:46:24.838
There are still roaches
in this place, Reynolds.

01:46:25.047 --> 01:46:28.133
- I killed one not five minutes ago.
- CARL: <i>I see. I....</i>

01:46:28.508 --> 01:46:30.344
Do you like your job, Reynolds?

01:46:30.635 --> 01:46:32.888
CARL: <i>Sir, I've spoken to Mr. White,
who's on desk tonight.</i>

01:46:33.096 --> 01:46:36.141
- Do you like your job, Reynolds?
- CARL: <i>Yes, sir.</i>

01:46:36.350 --> 01:46:38.769
I'm glad to hear it,
because I wanna see White.

01:46:39.019 --> 01:46:42.856
- CARL: <i>Mr. Pratt, it's almost quarter of ten--</i>
- And if I don't first see White...

01:46:43.065 --> 01:46:46.026
...and then the exterminators
within the space of a half an hour...

01:46:46.318 --> 01:46:48.695
...you will have no job
by midnight tonight, understand?

01:46:48.987 --> 01:46:52.657
Next year you can take the wife and kids
to Disney World on your welfare check.

01:46:52.908 --> 01:46:56.036
Have you got that?
Are we together on this?

01:46:57.412 --> 01:47:01.333
- CARL: <i>Yes, sir.</i>
- Good, I trust we are. Goodbye.

01:47:01.541 --> 01:47:03.293
♪♪

01:47:09.591 --> 01:47:11.051
You have to watch them.

01:47:11.885 --> 01:47:12.928
Oh, yes.

01:47:13.678 --> 01:47:16.098
<i>Castonmeyer, Reynolds...</i>

01:47:17.057 --> 01:47:17.974
...bugs.

01:47:19.559 --> 01:47:20.852
That's all they are.

01:47:21.603 --> 01:47:22.729
All of them.

01:47:31.154 --> 01:47:33.448
And although
they're essentially brainless...

01:47:34.282 --> 01:47:35.951
...you have to watch them...

01:47:36.910 --> 01:47:40.122
...because they creep up on you.

01:47:43.125 --> 01:47:44.292
They creep up on you.

01:47:44.501 --> 01:47:45.669
(lightning crashes)

01:48:07.107 --> 01:48:08.859
(electronic warbling)

01:48:25.542 --> 01:48:27.294
(doorbell ringing)

01:48:28.003 --> 01:48:29.713
PRATT:
Talk to me. Who's there?

01:48:30.088 --> 01:48:32.966
Good evening there, Mr. Pratt.

01:48:33.175 --> 01:48:35.927
Got bugs again, huh, Mr. Pratt?

01:48:36.136 --> 01:48:39.848
- Don't you talk to me like that, you hear?
- MAN: <i>What way, Mr. Pratt?</i>

01:48:40.056 --> 01:48:41.391
Like I was crazy.

01:48:41.600 --> 01:48:44.686
Oh, no, sir, Mr. Pratt, sir.

01:48:44.853 --> 01:48:47.898
I don't think you is crazy.
Not at all.

01:48:48.106 --> 01:48:50.233
I was just trying to run down
in my mind...

01:48:50.442 --> 01:48:53.320
...who might have
a 24-hour fumigating service.

01:48:53.612 --> 01:48:59.242
I might be able to get Pirelli Brothers
out here by, shall we say, 11:30?

01:48:59.451 --> 01:49:00.994
You might go far, White.

01:49:01.286 --> 01:49:06.583
I've noticed that in service jobs,
people like yourself often do.

01:49:07.000 --> 01:49:10.670
People of color.
Yes, 11:30 would be fine.

01:49:11.296 --> 01:49:14.508
Thanks, Mr. Pratt, sir.

01:49:14.716 --> 01:49:18.970
I'll call them just as soon as I finish
with that shower on 23.

01:49:19.387 --> 01:49:23.934
- Do it first. Do it now.
- Yes, sir. Right now.

01:49:25.227 --> 01:49:26.978
♪♪

01:49:29.898 --> 01:49:31.608
Only stunned.

01:49:31.942 --> 01:49:33.610
That's the explanation.

01:49:34.402 --> 01:49:38.657
Roaches are very hard to kill,
and they're quick.

01:49:39.241 --> 01:49:40.951
They can creep up on you.

01:49:41.660 --> 01:49:44.579
They can creep up on you
if you let them.

01:49:44.788 --> 01:49:46.540
(cockroaches skittering)

01:49:47.624 --> 01:49:48.583
(crunching)

01:49:57.884 --> 01:49:59.469
(hissing)

01:50:03.014 --> 01:50:07.394
See, Mrs. Castonmeyer,
I grew up in Hell's Kitchen.

01:50:07.769 --> 01:50:08.812
Bugs everywhere.

01:50:09.020 --> 01:50:09.688
(lightning crashes)

01:50:09.896 --> 01:50:12.732
PRATT: <i>I know what to do
with a bug when I see it.</i>

01:50:13.275 --> 01:50:17.571
Spray it. Squash it. Kill it.

01:50:20.490 --> 01:50:22.242
(lightning crashes)

01:50:22.450 --> 01:50:24.286
What the fuck?

01:50:25.245 --> 01:50:27.956
<i>Another son-of-a-bitching
blackout.</i>

01:50:29.583 --> 01:50:32.210
If it was my power company,
this would never happen.

01:50:32.419 --> 01:50:35.046
(lightning crashes)

01:50:38.216 --> 01:50:41.595
Bastards. Goddamn bugs.

01:50:41.803 --> 01:50:43.555
(cockroach skittering)

01:50:43.930 --> 01:50:44.973
Bastards!

01:50:45.181 --> 01:50:46.933
(cockroaches skittering)

01:50:49.436 --> 01:50:52.314
Fucking roaches. Goddamn b--

01:50:52.522 --> 01:50:53.148
(yelling)

01:50:53.356 --> 01:50:58.528
Bug bastards. I'll kill you,
you goddamn little bug-eyed--

01:50:58.737 --> 01:51:00.488
- (shouting)
- (cockroaches skittering)

01:51:01.573 --> 01:51:03.283
(lightning crashes)

01:51:03.450 --> 01:51:06.995
(alarm blaring)

01:51:07.203 --> 01:51:08.955
(cockroaches skittering)

01:51:18.965 --> 01:51:22.385
- (alarm stops)
- (cockroaches skittering)

01:51:24.095 --> 01:51:26.306
Come on, come on, come on.
What do I pay you for?

01:51:27.891 --> 01:51:28.600
(crunching)

01:51:31.353 --> 01:51:32.562
MAN: <i>Police, Emergency.</i>

01:51:32.771 --> 01:51:35.231
It's about time.
What are you people doing down there?

01:51:35.440 --> 01:51:36.900
MAN:
<i>We got problems tonight, fella.</i>

01:51:37.108 --> 01:51:40.570
<i>- Or haven't you looked out your window?</i>
- Listen, this is the Upson Pratt.

01:51:40.945 --> 01:51:41.905
<i>I've got bugs.</i>

01:51:42.113 --> 01:51:45.325
MAN: <i>Everybody's got bugs tonight,
and I don't have time for bullshit.</i>

01:51:45.533 --> 01:51:48.161
No, no, you don't understand.
These are cockroaches.

01:51:48.787 --> 01:51:52.749
The biggest ones I've ever seen.
It has gotta stop. It's gotta stop!

01:51:53.041 --> 01:51:56.086
MAN: <i>On a slow night we could talk
about it, but this isn't a slow night--</i>

01:51:56.378 --> 01:51:58.588
I don't think you understand
who you're talking to.

01:51:58.797 --> 01:52:01.841
This is Upson Pratt.
Upson Pratt!

01:52:02.050 --> 01:52:02.842
(line disconnects)

01:52:03.051 --> 01:52:06.012
I'll have your job, you asshole.
I'll have your--

01:52:06.221 --> 01:52:07.263
(shouting)

01:52:08.056 --> 01:52:09.182
(lightning crashes)

01:52:09.557 --> 01:52:12.102
White. White, talk to me.

01:52:12.310 --> 01:52:15.772
White. White, I know you can hear me.
The PA's on the emergency circuit.

01:52:15.980 --> 01:52:17.565
White, talk to me!

01:52:18.191 --> 01:52:22.737
- WHITE: <i>Mr. Pratt, I'm stuck in the damn elevator.</i>
- You can't be stuck in the elevator.

01:52:22.946 --> 01:52:25.448
I want you up here now.
There are roaches, hundreds of them.

01:52:25.782 --> 01:52:28.660
WHITE: <i>I'm gonna be here
till the power comes on. Sorry.</i>

01:52:28.868 --> 01:52:30.912
I'll have your job,
you black bastard.

01:52:31.121 --> 01:52:32.872
(cockroaches skittering)

01:52:40.046 --> 01:52:41.756
(lightning crashes)

01:52:53.268 --> 01:52:54.644
PRATT: <i>Come on, come on.</i>

01:53:00.608 --> 01:53:03.236
You'll never get in here.
Never.

01:53:03.445 --> 01:53:06.573
And when this blackout is over,
people are gonna pay. Oh, yes.

01:53:06.781 --> 01:53:10.952
And you'll pay too, every one of you.
Every damn one of you.

01:53:11.995 --> 01:53:15.123
I've been beating bugs all my life,
and I'll beat you, too.

01:53:15.415 --> 01:53:16.583
Bastards. Ba--

01:53:16.791 --> 01:53:17.876
(beeping)

01:53:18.752 --> 01:53:19.794
Talk to me.

01:53:20.754 --> 01:53:22.505
(skittering)

01:53:23.465 --> 01:53:27.761
LENORA: <i>Pratt, you old monster.
Oh, I hope you die.</i>

01:53:28.386 --> 01:53:29.929
<i>I hope you die.</i>

01:53:30.138 --> 01:53:33.099
<i>- I hope you die!</i>
- (cockroaches skittering)

01:53:33.308 --> 01:53:35.059
♪♪

01:53:37.854 --> 01:53:41.483
(shouting)

01:53:45.820 --> 01:53:48.782
LENORA:
<i>I hope you die.</i>

01:53:48.990 --> 01:53:52.952
COMPUTERIZED VOICE:
<i>It's 10:29-- It's 10-- It's 11 -- It's 12--</i>

01:53:53.161 --> 01:53:55.538
<i>It's 1 -- It's 2-- Four-- One-- It's 2--</i>

01:53:55.747 --> 01:54:00.335
<i>Three-- Four-- It's 4-- Four-- Two--
It's 4-- Four-- Three-- Four-- Four--</i>

01:54:00.543 --> 01:54:02.295
(sirens blaring)

01:54:03.546 --> 01:54:05.298
♪♪

01:54:10.553 --> 01:54:12.055
(doorbell ringing)

01:54:12.514 --> 01:54:13.973
WHITE:
<i>Mr. Pratt?</i>

01:54:14.474 --> 01:54:16.100
<i>You there, Mr. Pratt?</i>

01:54:17.060 --> 01:54:18.895
<i>Mr. Pratt? Talk to me.</i>

01:54:19.103 --> 01:54:20.730
- (computer warbling)
- (laughing)

01:54:20.939 --> 01:54:24.025
WHITE: <i>Talk to me,
talk to me. Honky bastard.</i>

01:54:25.318 --> 01:54:30.198
<i>What's the matter, Mr. Pratt?
Bugs got your tongue?</i>

01:54:31.491 --> 01:54:33.243
(rumbling)

01:54:36.496 --> 01:54:37.163
(chittering)

01:54:39.666 --> 01:54:41.417
(cockroaches skittering)

01:54:53.513 --> 01:54:55.223
(record playing last groove)

01:54:55.723 --> 01:54:59.519
- WHITE: Mr. Pratt. Mr. Pratt.
- (doorbell ringing)

01:55:00.603 --> 01:55:01.729
<i>Bastard.</i>

01:55:02.021 --> 01:55:04.232
♪♪

01:55:13.950 --> 01:55:15.702
(wind blowing)

01:55:17.203 --> 01:55:18.580
(lightning crashes)

01:55:24.794 --> 01:55:26.337
(garbage can clattering)

01:55:26.546 --> 01:55:27.922
(whistling, shouting)

01:55:41.311 --> 01:55:42.103
(garbage can clattering)

01:55:42.312 --> 01:55:44.314
Now eat, you bigmouth.

01:55:49.652 --> 01:55:50.361
(garbage can lid clattering)

01:55:50.570 --> 01:55:53.031
Chew your food
before you swallow!

01:55:55.742 --> 01:55:57.744
- What's that?
- It's a comic book.

01:55:57.952 --> 01:55:58.912
What?

01:55:59.120 --> 01:56:00.580
- It's a comic book.
- What?

01:56:00.788 --> 01:56:02.874
- It's a comic book!
- A comic book!

01:56:03.499 --> 01:56:05.627
MAN 1: My kids love these things.
MAN 2: I love them too.

01:56:05.835 --> 01:56:08.713
Hey, look, look. You can
send away for all this stuff here.

01:56:08.922 --> 01:56:11.799
- Look, x-ray glasses.
- They don't work.

01:56:12.008 --> 01:56:14.677
They make your eyes black.
You look in and it's a gag, you know?

01:56:16.262 --> 01:56:19.265
Look, an authentic voodoo doll.

01:56:19.682 --> 01:56:22.936
- Somebody already sent for it.
- Yeah, we can't get that.

01:56:23.144 --> 01:56:23.811
How about this?

01:56:24.020 --> 01:56:26.439
"Tired of getting sand
kicked in your face?"

01:56:26.773 --> 01:56:28.274
(chuckling)

01:56:30.068 --> 01:56:31.027
Where's Billy?

01:56:31.527 --> 01:56:33.613
He'll be down in a minute.
I know he's up.

01:56:34.155 --> 01:56:35.531
Billy?

01:56:35.907 --> 01:56:37.408
Stan, are you all right?

01:56:39.535 --> 01:56:41.704
I didn't get much sleep
last night.

01:56:42.163 --> 01:56:43.289
The storm?

01:56:44.040 --> 01:56:47.251
No, it's this goddamn stiff neck.
I can barely move my head.

01:56:47.794 --> 01:56:49.003
Well, you must have strained it.

01:56:49.629 --> 01:56:52.548
Yeah. Yeah, I guess. I don't know.

01:56:52.757 --> 01:56:53.758
(groans)

01:56:53.967 --> 01:56:56.427
Well, you poor old bear.
You want me to get some Bengay?

01:56:56.636 --> 01:56:58.930
No. No.

01:56:59.847 --> 01:57:02.976
- (puncturing)
- (groaning)

01:57:03.184 --> 01:57:05.770
I'll teach him
to throw away my comic books.

01:57:05.979 --> 01:57:10.441
- (puncturing continues)
- (groaning continues)

01:57:10.858 --> 01:57:13.569
Ready for another shot, Dad?

01:57:13.778 --> 01:57:15.530
♪♪

01:57:27.959 --> 01:57:30.670
(cackling laughter)

01:58:34.984 --> 01:58:36.736
♪♪

02:00:09.745 --> 02:00:11.664
(cackling laughter)
